WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:15.451 --> 00:00:17.820
﻿Plasma Youth Sports Games
with Unsuccess of the champion,

00:00:17.921 --> 00:00:20.375
would like to thank Slaven Bilić
for stepping in as the host.

00:00:20.442 --> 00:00:23.452
Bilić is one of the first sponsors,
ambassador and is our biggest promoter.

00:00:23.586 --> 00:00:26.617
He used his life and sports experience
in order to prepare high-quality content

00:00:26.811 --> 00:00:29.778
with his guests for all generations.
Thanks, Nane!

00:00:32.616 --> 00:00:35.311
That relationship of yours
with the players...

00:00:36.719 --> 00:00:41.750
When I was in Beşiktaş in 2014,
and you were in Fenerbahçe,

00:00:42.340 --> 00:00:45.540
you played an exhibition game
against the San Antonio Spurs. -Yes.

00:00:47.340 --> 00:00:51.980
At that time, Luka Žorić (Žora)
and Bojan Bogdanović were playing,

00:00:52.191 --> 00:00:55.711
and on my coaching staff, I had
Miljenko Rak, who loved basketball.

00:00:55.833 --> 00:00:58.753
That's right. -He's the Frank
Sinatra of Croatian sports,

00:00:58.889 --> 00:01:01.169
and I want to greet him.

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:07.260
Then Žora spoke about those
situations with enthusiasm.

00:01:07.780 --> 00:01:11.940
He told us about those moments
when he would go out,

00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:16.300
and you wouldn't just see him
and greet him, but you'd

00:01:16.540 --> 00:01:18.500
invite him to your table.

00:01:18.740 --> 00:01:22.340
But the next day in Ataşehir,
it was as if nothing had happened.

00:01:23.104 --> 00:01:26.637
Only work mattered.
That's what's fascinating.

00:01:29.780 --> 00:01:34.980
You yourself said a moment ago
that you're not easy to work with.

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:38.100
And at the same time,
you say that you don't just have

00:01:38.300 --> 00:01:41.860
two children, but 17 or 170.

00:01:43.100 --> 00:01:45.340
What you said...

00:01:47.740 --> 00:01:51.020
What I want to say is more
of a thought than a question,

00:01:51.340 --> 00:01:54.420
but I think I'm right,
and I'm glad about it.

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:59.074
When a person watches short
clips of you, they will think-

00:01:59.219 --> 00:02:02.269
and you often say it yourself-
that you're surprised

00:02:02.417 --> 00:02:04.988
and you wonder, "What this is?"
-That's right.

00:02:05.118 --> 00:02:09.879
You say, "Aleksa," or "Do you want me
to hit you with the clipboard?"

00:02:10.124 --> 00:02:12.484
A person might think
you've lost your mind.

00:02:12.732 --> 00:02:17.212
However, when someone watches
a podcast or a longer statement,

00:02:17.438 --> 00:02:20.598
they can see that there's a lot of empathy,
love, intelligence, wisdom,

00:02:20.798 --> 00:02:23.921
so much energy, but also calmness.

00:02:24.620 --> 00:02:29.780
Then I realized that your
relationship is complete.

00:02:30.140 --> 00:02:32.060
And you just demand everything.

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:34.940
When something is complete,
it has both sides.

00:02:35.140 --> 00:02:38.700
And Aleksa will tolerate it when
you yell at him, just because

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:42.580
he knows you have
that other side too.

00:02:43.940 --> 00:02:48.260
Because I can lightly hit my own child,
but I can't hit the neighbor's child.

00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:53.460
And you can behave like that towards
them because you give them everything.

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:56.574
You have a complete relationship
with them, and that drains

00:02:56.726 --> 00:02:59.406
and consumes energy.
-You're right.

00:02:59.652 --> 00:03:02.341
But without that, it's not possible,
or at least I can't do it.

00:03:02.501 --> 00:03:06.474
I tried to explain to the players
that while I'm addressing them,

00:03:06.599 --> 00:03:08.479
I'm interested in them.

00:03:08.588 --> 00:03:11.466
When I stop addressing them,
it means they're no longer important to me.

00:03:11.542 --> 00:03:13.462
I'm always looking for better results.

00:03:13.626 --> 00:03:18.263
Otherwise, all those scenes during
timeouts are an integral part of the job.

00:03:19.078 --> 00:03:21.118
But I don't think it's fair.

00:03:21.250 --> 00:03:23.747
I don't have a problem with
whether it's broadcast or not.

00:03:23.897 --> 00:03:30.617
But in the NBA, which is the best
competition, they create sequences

00:03:30.843 --> 00:03:33.123
that are allowed to be broadcast.

00:03:33.268 --> 00:03:35.692
What I want to say is, everything
is recorded, but only one part

00:03:35.843 --> 00:03:37.723
of the conversation is broadcast.

00:03:37.908 --> 00:03:43.707
If I could, I'd like to go into someone's
office here and record them.

00:03:44.148 --> 00:03:46.308
What would we hear then? -Yes.

00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:50.225
Let's go to someone's house when
the family is sitting at the table

00:03:50.371 --> 00:03:52.571
eating lunch, and when the father
talks to the children or his wife,

00:03:52.709 --> 00:03:54.189
what would we hear then?

00:03:54.295 --> 00:03:58.874
I don't have any problem with it.
Those I address like that know it.

00:03:59.807 --> 00:04:02.327
I want to go back to Žora's story.

00:04:02.820 --> 00:04:06.060
I've been doing this my whole life
because I'm that kind of person.

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:10.300
When we're out somewhere,
they are my best friends.

00:04:10.540 --> 00:04:13.940
I'm talking about the coaching staff.
We enjoy life.

00:04:14.180 --> 00:04:16.980
When we enter the hall, someone
has put me there to be the one

00:04:17.180 --> 00:04:20.460
who gives guidelines and directions.

00:04:20.700 --> 00:04:22.900
And we have to know that.

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:25.740
When we're outside, we're equal.

00:04:25.980 --> 00:04:28.340
If you came and sat on my head,
I wouldn't have a problem with it.

00:04:28.580 --> 00:04:30.980
When we enter the hall,
I'm the one who determines

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:35.020
what we'll do and how we'll do it.
Of course, in cooperation with others.

00:04:35.260 --> 00:04:38.260
Others have the right to an opinion,
especially the players.

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:42.500
I say my opinion, but in the end,
we will all move in the same direction.

00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:44.740
If someone goes one way
and someone else goes the other,

00:04:44.940 --> 00:04:47.060
then nothing will come of that job.

00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:50.700
I give to the players,
but I also demand from them.

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:54.961
That's exactly it. It's true that
I demand a lot. But I know why I do it.

00:04:55.098 --> 00:04:57.338
When I give a player everything,
I have the right to ask

00:04:57.500 --> 00:04:59.420
for the same from him.

00:04:59.568 --> 00:05:02.488
That's the only way...
Is there greater happiness than...

00:05:02.658 --> 00:05:07.000
Now we've returned after these
two days, and at the airport,

00:05:07.172 --> 00:05:09.555
we were greeted in the morning...

00:05:09.769 --> 00:05:12.449
I think it was 2:30 a.m.,
and there were many Partizan fans.

00:05:12.594 --> 00:05:14.649
Two weeks ago,
the same thing happened.

00:05:14.806 --> 00:05:16.926
It was 5:00 a.m, and there
were even more fans.

00:05:17.195 --> 00:05:21.399
Does any of us have the right to put
a finger to our forehead and wonder?

00:05:21.629 --> 00:05:24.229
Imagine how beautiful this is
that we're doing, when we've made

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:26.280
so many people happy.

00:05:27.300 --> 00:05:29.900
Is there anything more
beautiful than that? -No.

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:34.380
Do you compare basketball
with other sports?

00:05:34.651 --> 00:05:38.971
Of course, the motivation is the same,
but do you use other sports

00:05:39.396 --> 00:05:43.362
in a tactical sense?
The late Ivić used handball.

00:05:44.112 --> 00:05:48.872
It's great to step out
on a player who has the ball.

00:05:49.104 --> 00:05:52.104
The others make corrections,
leaving free space on the wings,

00:05:52.337 --> 00:05:55.659
but the principle is the same
as in football.

00:05:55.860 --> 00:06:00.860
Or, for example, England
coach Southgate used the NFL

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:04.980
as an example for some set pieces
or certain situations. -I understand.

00:06:05.180 --> 00:06:10.900
Do you follow other sports?
-Every top sport is beautiful to watch.

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:14.060
What is the essence of top sports?
That while you're watching it,

00:06:14.260 --> 00:06:17.740
you think you can do it too.
That's something fascinating.

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:22.020
I know that Ivić used pressing
from basketball as an example.

00:06:22.260 --> 00:06:26.180
Because Hajduk played pressing
all over the field at that time.

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:31.420
I don't want to go into detail about
football and zonal defenses now.

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:35.260
How to defend with ten players.

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:39.140
With Guardiola, the goalkeeper
must know how to play

00:06:39.340 --> 00:06:40.820
well with his feet.

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:45.780
I'm lucky to have
many friends in all sports.

00:06:46.060 --> 00:06:49.460
I have many friends
who play water polo.

00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:53.260
And I talk a lot with them.
Water polo is a specific sport.

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:57.660
Veselin Vujović was once the best
handball player in the world,

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:01.900
and later became a coach.
And I tried to explain to my dear Vujo.

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:08.260
Vujo, don't expect the players
to be like you. That's the trick.

00:07:11.940 --> 00:07:17.460
Aggressiveness is something
that in those sports where

00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:20.485
there is contact, and I mean
football, basketball, handball,

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:25.260
you can achieve
something with that.

00:07:27.064 --> 00:07:32.046
Even in handball, there are blocks
similar to those in basketball.

00:07:32.380 --> 00:07:36.260
Not as much, but they exist.
And there, they play two against two.

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:41.820
In football, during set pieces, players
make blocks for each other. -Exactly.

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:49.580
That's why it's used. -Space
is very important in basketball.

00:07:50.036 --> 00:07:51.836
Space and timing.

00:07:52.740 --> 00:07:56.220
And I can imagine how it is
in football, on such a large space.

00:07:56.420 --> 00:08:00.780
How important space is in football.
If we have... You have less.

00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:02.420
That's right.

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:05.780
Imagine how much you
footballers work on space.

00:08:06.020 --> 00:08:10.980
So there are points of contact.
We're talking about tactics.

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:15.020
Not to mention psychology,
togetherness, team, etc.

00:08:15.220 --> 00:08:16.620
That's roughly it.

00:08:16.860 --> 00:08:20.420
When I think about basketball,
handball, and water polo,

00:08:20.700 --> 00:08:25.820
for you, the middle of the field is
a transit zone. -Almost irrelevant.

00:08:26.060 --> 00:08:28.660
You have offense and defense.

00:08:28.900 --> 00:08:38.300
So you can draw an action that will bring
your player into an opportunity.

00:08:38.540 --> 00:08:41.887
Whether to be alone on the shot
or in a goal-scoring opportunity.

00:08:42.037 --> 00:08:46.168
Or play one-on-one, but he's the best.
And you expect him to solve it.

00:08:46.363 --> 00:08:50.153
Yes. -In football, that's difficult.
-It's different. I can draw a goal.

00:08:50.866 --> 00:08:54.418
But it's not the same.
The only solution is an extra player.

00:08:54.564 --> 00:08:59.067
The essence of every sport
is to create an extra player.

00:09:00.060 --> 00:09:06.620
You insist on focus, don't you?
-That's right.

00:09:06.860 --> 00:09:09.620
Focus is the most important.
-Yes. Easy baskets.

00:09:09.780 --> 00:09:13.660
Concentration. It's the same
in football, but it's also...

00:09:13.900 --> 00:09:16.420
You always insist that how you
train is how you play,

00:09:16.660 --> 00:09:18.260
you always have to move
on your toes.

00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:21.100
If someone scores a basket,
he starts to celebrate...

00:09:21.340 --> 00:09:23.700
During that time,
there's a counterattack.

00:09:23.980 --> 00:09:25.980
How I look at it.

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:29.020
For you, at any moment
when you lose the ball,

00:09:29.220 --> 00:09:36.500
a late reaction from your player
leads to an undefendable counterattack.

00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:41.300
And in football, it's different,
if the midfielder on the right wing

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:47.100
didn't pass the ball, he can stay back,
the defender can create an extra player.

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:51.020
He'll react, "Why did you pass
the ball like that to me?"

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:56.020
You won't be happy, however,
it rarely results in a goal.

00:09:56.300 --> 00:09:59.380
Because behind him, there are still
nine or seven players.

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:03.580
It's much easier to play like that.

00:10:04.260 --> 00:10:12.020
The similarities are as follows:
footballers have a huge desire

00:10:12.135 --> 00:10:14.055
to run and score a goal.

00:10:14.303 --> 00:10:16.394
But they don't have the same
desire to defend. -Certainly.

00:10:16.581 --> 00:10:18.021
It's the same in basketball.

00:10:18.159 --> 00:10:20.078
Everyone wants to run
in the counterattack,

00:10:20.187 --> 00:10:22.027
but no one wants to run
back to defend.

00:10:22.292 --> 00:10:25.132
And again, we're talking about
the level of the ball

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:27.220
and the extra player
in defense and attack.

00:10:27.312 --> 00:10:29.232
The more players there are,
the easier everything is.

00:10:29.369 --> 00:10:30.961
It's probably the same in football.

00:10:31.113 --> 00:10:35.117
Many attacking players don't want
to block the opposing player in time,

00:10:35.208 --> 00:10:37.168
and an easy goal is conceded.

00:10:37.313 --> 00:10:42.375
Especially since today in football,
the transition game is emphasized.

00:10:42.549 --> 00:10:46.829
You probably advise players
to play faster after defense.

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:50.550
We talked a moment ago about
how much faster the ball

00:10:50.751 --> 00:10:53.711
is than the player.
-Yes. -That's it.

00:10:56.460 --> 00:11:01.180
What I insist on in basketball
and the players

00:11:01.460 --> 00:11:06.980
know is timing, space, and time.

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:11.820
Without that, there's
no good basketball. No way.

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:15.620
Later come the details, blocks,
at what angle and how.

00:11:19.980 --> 00:11:24.300
Three days ago, a friend sent me
a recording of a game.

00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:28.060
The game was played in Belgrade
in 1984 between Partizan and Cibona,

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:29.900
where we won by two points.

00:11:30.100 --> 00:11:32.500
That was the first year
I came to Partizan.

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:38.460
Moka was the coach, and Dražen,
Aco, Knego, Čutura, Ušić, Nakić,

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:43.660
Bečić played in Cibona.
It was a phenomenal team.

00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:48.220
Watching that game,
I noticed that there was no blocks.

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:52.660
And today someone asks the question,
has basketball changed?

00:11:55.298 --> 00:11:58.176
They mainly played
zonal defense, as did we.

00:11:58.645 --> 00:12:02.355
I don't remember playing
two games this year

00:12:03.996 --> 00:12:06.829
where the opposing team tried
to play zonal defense.

00:12:07.279 --> 00:12:12.293
Maybe there were two such defenses
the whole season, and now we're

00:12:13.180 --> 00:12:16.420
playing the twenty-sixth round.

00:12:16.607 --> 00:12:18.866
And once only zonal defense
was played.

00:12:18.968 --> 00:12:21.287
And the second thing is that
all players are inside.

00:12:21.404 --> 00:12:23.204
The progress is noticeable.

00:12:23.700 --> 00:12:27.460
That year, the rule was changed,
and they introduced three points.

00:12:27.740 --> 00:12:30.300
And they introduced the line on the court
after the Los Angeles Olympics.

00:12:30.390 --> 00:12:31.750
That happened in 1984.

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:34.900
At that time, when someone scored
three points, it was a big deal.

00:12:35.220 --> 00:12:37.940
Today it's like a layup,
like going for a layup.

00:12:38.940 --> 00:12:44.380
Tell me, in your opinion,
is basketball a fairer sport

00:12:44.660 --> 00:12:47.740
than football when it
comes to results?

00:12:48.020 --> 00:12:50.580
In football, it often happens
that we lose a game,

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:53.420
and sometimes we win in such a way.
But when we lose,

00:12:53.660 --> 00:12:57.020
we say that in basketball,
we would have won by ten points.

00:12:57.220 --> 00:12:58.820
But here it's 0:1.

00:12:59.540 --> 00:13:02.660
When it comes to basketball, it seems
to me that the better team always wins.

00:13:02.860 --> 00:13:06.780
Not better on paper,
but better on the court that day.

00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:11.100
Basketball is a specific sport
because the game cannot end in a draw.

00:13:11.820 --> 00:13:16.020
Someone always has to win.
But there are such similarities.

00:13:16.166 --> 00:13:18.646
Sometimes a team plays well
but still loses.

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:20.880
Concedes a basket in the last second.

00:13:21.380 --> 00:13:24.700
You play a good game,
but then something happens...

00:13:25.580 --> 00:13:30.780
This year, my team conceded
baskets in the final seconds.

00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:36.300
In one game we lost, we conceded
12 points in the last second.

00:13:36.580 --> 00:13:40.380
The ball simply hits the backboard
after the shot and goes in.

00:13:41.300 --> 00:13:44.940
It's some higher power.
But no matter-we move on.

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:49.620
Sometimes we got lucky too.
It all evens out in the end.

00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:55.682
In football, refereeing is one
of the most important factors.

00:13:56.131 --> 00:14:00.094
VAR has helped make
the game fairer.

00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:06.020
But even with VAR, some
decisions are made-or not made.

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:08.940
You know that better than I do.

00:14:09.180 --> 00:14:12.338
To me, as an ordinary viewer,
some decisions aren't clear.

00:14:12.567 --> 00:14:15.525
They often say VAR didn't react,
so why didn't the referee?

00:14:19.940 --> 00:14:26.732
Does it seem to you,
or is the grass always greener

00:14:27.022 --> 00:14:29.462
on the neighbor's side than on ours?

00:14:29.931 --> 00:14:36.651
However, my opinion,
it's easier to keep players satisfied

00:14:37.180 --> 00:14:39.940
in basketball than in football.

00:14:40.180 --> 00:14:44.180
Because the squad is smaller,
and there's also more rotation.

00:14:44.270 --> 00:14:47.880
Because when will I bring my fifth
center-back into the game?

00:14:47.980 --> 00:14:50.745
He has to wait for his chance.
-For someone to get injured.

00:14:50.886 --> 00:14:54.042
Maybe for someone to get a card,
be in bad form, or get injured.

00:14:54.345 --> 00:14:58.945
And in basketball, you can...
-I agree. In basketball, it's different.

00:14:59.050 --> 00:15:00.650
That team spirit.

00:15:00.788 --> 00:15:05.708
You have 12 players and it's been
known for several seasons

00:15:05.964 --> 00:15:10.003
that in every team has several players
missing due to injuries or something else.

00:15:10.193 --> 00:15:12.425
And then other players get a chance.

00:15:12.980 --> 00:15:15.980
Of course, it depends on them
how they take the opportunity,

00:15:16.180 --> 00:15:20.220
but I agree it's easier in basketball.

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:22.580
Especially because it's a more
dynamic sport in the sense

00:15:22.780 --> 00:15:24.260
that you can make substitutions.

00:15:24.460 --> 00:15:26.620
Because in football,
once you make a substitution,

00:15:26.820 --> 00:15:29.060
you can't bring the player back.

00:15:29.220 --> 00:15:30.980
I think it's good thing today
in football, you have

00:15:31.180 --> 00:15:32.820
the right to more substitutions.

00:15:32.980 --> 00:15:34.500
Earlier, you were only allowed two.
-There were three...

00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:37.100
At first two, then three
for a long time, and now five.

00:15:37.300 --> 00:15:39.940
With five, you can already...
-Do what you want.

00:15:40.164 --> 00:15:43.586
Change tactics and everything else.
-That gives coaches a lot...

00:15:43.762 --> 00:15:45.362
And in basketball, that's it.

00:15:45.578 --> 00:15:47.945
You have the right to substitute
a player for just two seconds.

00:15:48.211 --> 00:15:53.571
Of course, before that,
you have to explain to them...

00:15:54.093 --> 00:15:56.653
Substitutions are not only made
when someone plays poorly.

00:15:56.829 --> 00:15:59.217
That's not the only
type of substitution.

00:15:59.358 --> 00:16:01.912
There are 1.000 other reasons for
substitutions. -That's right!

00:16:02.122 --> 00:16:04.717
If the players know and understand
that, then that is all there is to it.

00:16:04.902 --> 00:16:07.999
In basketball, by default,
when you concede a basket

00:16:08.170 --> 00:16:10.410
in the last two minutes, you can
automatically request a substitution.

00:16:10.516 --> 00:16:12.616
Substitutions are made
to slow down the pace,

00:16:12.706 --> 00:16:14.946
to prevent the other team from
switching to a full-court press.

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:18.140
I understand... -You also make
substitutions after free throws...

00:16:18.262 --> 00:16:22.262
There are many reasons for it,
and coaches take advantage of that.

00:16:23.066 --> 00:16:27.546
The review rule is sometimes used
just to avoid wasting a timeout.

00:16:27.730 --> 00:16:31.130
You ask for a play to be reviewed even
when you know the call was correct,

00:16:31.260 --> 00:16:33.256
just to get a chance
to draw up a play,

00:16:33.540 --> 00:16:37.020
to give your players a breather
without officially calling a timeout.

00:16:37.300 --> 00:16:42.100
Yes, yes... Tell me, please,
once a great coach of Real Madrid

00:16:42.340 --> 00:16:45.460
and Manchester City,
now at Betis, Pellegrini. -I know.

00:16:45.700 --> 00:16:52.660
...he said that a coach's influence
in football is 95% during training,

00:16:53.100 --> 00:16:57.580
but only 5% during the match. Is
that percentage higher in basketball

00:16:57.780 --> 00:17:01.940
because you're closer to the players,
you have substitutions, timeouts,

00:17:02.140 --> 00:17:06.020
and you can whisper something
to someone during free throws?

00:17:06.220 --> 00:17:10.180
Even with challenges,
you have more opportunities to...

00:17:10.460 --> 00:17:12.860
In football, you often wait for
halftime or a serious injury

00:17:13.100 --> 00:17:18.940
to say something to your players.
-I think basketball is a sport

00:17:19.220 --> 00:17:21.860
where coaches have a significant
influence during the game.

00:17:22.100 --> 00:17:26.087
It's just the nature of the sport.
It has substitutions, timeouts,

00:17:26.522 --> 00:17:29.482
and the speed at which the game is
played-coaches can influence

00:17:29.691 --> 00:17:32.451
the outcome much more, I believe,
than in any other sport.

00:17:33.340 --> 00:17:35.893
I can't speak about other sports
because I don't know them as well,

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:38.920
but I know that here, we as coaches
definitely have a major impact.

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:41.740
Apart from your preparation
before the game,

00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:45.140
what you do during the game
is extremely important.

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:48.060
The role of the coach in
those moments is invaluable. -Yes.

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:51.540
Everybody knows that,
and smart players know that too.

00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:54.100
All those decisions you make...
You have to think quickly,

00:17:54.300 --> 00:17:56.260
you have to know your team
as well as the opponent's,

00:17:56.500 --> 00:17:59.860
you have to react to substitutions...
We have this saying in basketball:

00:18:00.060 --> 00:18:01.660
"He didn't respond to me."

00:18:01.736 --> 00:18:03.976
For example, the opposing team
starts a new play with three big men

00:18:04.137 --> 00:18:06.071
while you're playing
with three smaller players.

00:18:06.196 --> 00:18:08.356
You must have a reason for
sticking with the smaller lineup

00:18:08.485 --> 00:18:09.845
while he's using the big ones.

00:18:09.968 --> 00:18:12.084
And then, if he wins, they say,
"You didn't respond to him."

00:18:12.207 --> 00:18:14.655
But if you don't respond and still
win, they say, "You outsmarted him."

00:18:14.777 --> 00:18:16.826
The winner is always the one
who comes out on top.

00:18:16.979 --> 00:18:19.994
Now we also have these expert
analysts and all these smart people

00:18:20.147 --> 00:18:23.067
who know everything, but of course,
they always speak up after the game.

00:18:23.237 --> 00:18:25.058
And then you feel like asking them,

00:18:25.208 --> 00:18:27.316
"Why don't you come and sit
on this bench for a while?

00:18:27.465 --> 00:18:29.325
Let's see how you handle it here."

00:18:29.477 --> 00:18:32.037
It's easy to analyze everything
after the game-we all know that.

00:18:32.472 --> 00:18:37.557
Tell me, when it comes to coaching,
people always talk about two things:

00:18:38.393 --> 00:18:41.323
one is knowledge of the game,
whether it's basketball, football,

00:18:41.486 --> 00:18:46.714
water polo, handball-and the
other is psychology, management,

00:18:46.896 --> 00:18:48.816
relationships with players,
and all that.

00:18:48.906 --> 00:18:51.026
Some are better at one thing,
others at the other.

00:18:51.173 --> 00:18:54.493
How do you see that? Is there
something you find more important?

00:18:55.380 --> 00:18:58.700
More decisive, perhaps?
-Both are important.

00:18:59.740 --> 00:19:04.090
The foundation is to have knowledge
and the authority that comes from

00:19:04.355 --> 00:19:07.239
that knowledge-something players,
above all, recognize.

00:19:07.392 --> 00:19:09.472
That's the first prerequisite.

00:19:09.713 --> 00:19:12.825
If you don't have that, then you can't
do anything; it just doesn't work.

00:19:13.002 --> 00:19:16.082
And then, of course, it's about
building relationships with players,

00:19:16.229 --> 00:19:18.973
where they need to understand
that you genuinely care about them

00:19:19.173 --> 00:19:22.333
and that you're looking out for them.
But at the end of the day,

00:19:22.473 --> 00:19:26.633
I always emphasize to them
that my primary interest is

00:19:26.824 --> 00:19:29.833
the one that stands above
all others-the team's interest.

00:19:30.111 --> 00:19:33.610
None of them can be more important
than the team itself.

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:36.460
That's where everything
begins and ends. -Yes.

00:19:36.700 --> 00:19:40.460
Maintaining that balance isn't easy,
but you have to work on it.

00:19:40.659 --> 00:19:43.699
You have to convince them
and communicate with them daily.

00:19:44.135 --> 00:19:46.907
Many times, and we've already
mentioned this several times

00:19:47.050 --> 00:19:49.595
in this conversation,
you say it once, you say it again.

00:19:49.783 --> 00:19:52.493
Sometimes you have to say it 5 times,
10 times, 15 times, 20 times...

00:19:52.682 --> 00:19:56.149
I even have this saying: "I've said it
a million and one times,"

00:19:56.251 --> 00:19:57.837
but sometimes even that isn't enough.

00:19:57.935 --> 00:19:59.865
What can you do?
That's just how things are.

00:20:00.132 --> 00:20:03.685
That's essentially what Ferguson
says-you're the decision-maker,

00:20:03.851 --> 00:20:06.851
you have to make decisions.
When I look back at my career,

00:20:07.904 --> 00:20:12.184
everything good or bad that happened
to me, 95% of it was the result of

00:20:12.659 --> 00:20:16.099
whether I made a decision,
what kind of decision I made,

00:20:16.252 --> 00:20:19.212
or whether I didn't make one at all.
It's less about whether we played

00:20:19.357 --> 00:20:24.161
4-2-3-1 or 3-5-2; it all comes down
to the day-to-day decisions,

00:20:24.285 --> 00:20:27.661
whether they're comfortable or
uncomfortable, easy or difficult.

00:20:29.726 --> 00:20:31.958
It's just that simple.

00:20:32.995 --> 00:20:41.432
However, as Ferguson says, "adapt or
die", and we discussed that earlier.

00:20:41.647 --> 00:20:46.007
But how much has the job changed,
not in terms of dealing with players,

00:20:46.167 --> 00:20:49.979
we already covered that-but in terms
of demands from the management,

00:20:50.124 --> 00:20:54.804
from the fans, and the media, now that
everyone seems to know everything?

00:20:54.958 --> 00:20:56.878
And then there's this new mentality,

00:20:56.993 --> 00:20:59.596
which I see in my kids
that want the holy trinity:

00:20:59.686 --> 00:21:04.292
"give it to me now, give me
everything, and keep on giving."

00:21:05.593 --> 00:21:11.268
Impatience is definitely there,
and that's just the nature of our job.

00:21:12.980 --> 00:21:18.020
I was fortunate enough
never to be fired as a coach.

00:21:18.740 --> 00:21:21.980
Any breaks I took were my decisions.

00:21:22.180 --> 00:21:28.380
Like when I took a year off after
Panathinaikos or Fenerbahçe...

00:21:30.260 --> 00:21:34.140
I believe that public impatience,

00:21:34.660 --> 00:21:39.700
whether from fans or others
who have certain interests,

00:21:39.940 --> 00:21:44.380
maybe because they want to bring in
a different coach-is always present.

00:21:45.300 --> 00:21:48.380
However, those who have been
patient with their coaches

00:21:48.860 --> 00:21:52.740
and the clubs where coaches
have stayed for a longer period

00:21:52.980 --> 00:21:56.340
have always seen good results.
-Yes. -That's the essence of it.

00:21:56.820 --> 00:21:59.700
Of course, when we talk
about good results,

00:21:59.900 --> 00:22:04.060
it always comes down to what the
goals are, what the objectives are.

00:22:04.460 --> 00:22:09.540
And it's not just in basketball.
Take football, for example,

00:22:09.820 --> 00:22:12.780
everyone knows who the favorites are,
and everyone knows which teams are

00:22:13.060 --> 00:22:17.100
expected to be at least in the top 8,
or the top 4, or the finals.

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:21.700
A club like Real Madrid,
arguably the best club in the world,

00:22:21.940 --> 00:22:24.580
won't be satisfied just by
reaching the top 4 in Europe.

00:22:24.820 --> 00:22:28.060
No one in the world would call that
a good result. That's just how it is.

00:22:28.181 --> 00:22:30.180
Not even if they finish second...

00:22:30.469 --> 00:22:33.429
But there's one thing
I've always pointed out...

00:22:34.068 --> 00:22:41.988
Michael Jordan played, what,
15 seasons in the NBA?

00:22:42.318 --> 00:22:44.198
He was a champion six times.

00:22:44.571 --> 00:22:47.706
Does that mean he was unsuccessful
in the other nine seasons? -Yeah...

00:22:49.043 --> 00:22:51.403
I don't think so.
Somebody has to win.

00:22:51.572 --> 00:22:54.052
Now we have the EuroLeague, 18 teams,
it's a phenomenal competition,

00:22:54.244 --> 00:22:56.265
but only one can be the champion.

00:22:56.414 --> 00:23:00.147
Does that mean all the other teams
were failures? I don't think so,

00:23:01.139 --> 00:23:06.115
but the way sports are today,
they demand victories, victories...

00:23:06.420 --> 00:23:11.500
You have club presidents and others
who are patient, who understand,

00:23:11.664 --> 00:23:16.844
who are objective-which isn't easy,
it's not easy to provide support,

00:23:17.375 --> 00:23:22.060
and then you have others who become
impatient at the start of the season.

00:23:23.447 --> 00:23:27.963
I've always said... The season starts,
and after just three or four rounds,

00:23:28.516 --> 00:23:30.721
the president fires the coach.

00:23:31.392 --> 00:23:35.632
So, who's at fault-the coach
or the president? You chose him.

00:23:35.913 --> 00:23:39.041
You must have made the wrong decision
if you're replacing him so quickly.

00:23:39.300 --> 00:23:42.276
Or take my own example,
at the start of this season,

00:23:42.387 --> 00:23:46.784
we were 2-8 in the EuroLeague.
Should I have replaced the players?

00:23:47.447 --> 00:23:51.287
Should I have said we're playing
poorly because they're playing poorly?

00:23:51.511 --> 00:23:54.551
No, I believed in those players,
and I still believe in them to this day.

00:23:54.656 --> 00:23:57.120
It's the same situation
with the relationship between

00:23:57.193 --> 00:23:59.932
the club and the coach as it is
with the coach and the players,

00:24:00.078 --> 00:24:01.461
it's about patience.

00:24:01.592 --> 00:24:03.752
I chose you,
and I believe in you.

00:24:03.929 --> 00:24:08.889
I tell them, "Look, I can't be
against you. Why? Because I chose you.

00:24:09.027 --> 00:24:11.557
Of course, you also
chose me and my club.

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:13.680
If I chose you,
that means I trust you,

00:24:13.900 --> 00:24:16.100
and I will continue to trust you."

00:24:16.340 --> 00:24:19.740
A lot of time has to pass, or
something extraordinary has to happen,

00:24:19.940 --> 00:24:22.580
for me to give up on a player,
let alone stop talking to him...

00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:25.024
If we stop talking,
then that's the end,

00:24:25.306 --> 00:24:27.769
it's better for him
to find a new place.

00:24:28.258 --> 00:24:31.500
These days, people often
talk about pressure,

00:24:31.700 --> 00:24:34.248
not just in sports but in life.

00:24:35.020 --> 00:24:39.588
Do you think that the pressure
has become too much

00:24:40.200 --> 00:24:43.986
because of social media,
Instagram, and all of that,

00:24:44.741 --> 00:24:47.221
especially for players and coaches?

00:24:47.666 --> 00:24:50.752
Part of your job is to help
relieve that pressure a bit.

00:24:50.960 --> 00:24:54.971
I saw this fascinating example
a few years ago

00:24:55.221 --> 00:24:58.015
while watching a Premier League.
Liverpool was playing against someone,

00:24:58.318 --> 00:25:01.598
and one of their players,
someone who obviously already has

00:25:02.260 --> 00:25:05.700
a certain level of mental strength,
was being interviewed after the match.

00:25:05.980 --> 00:25:09.969
I guess he played poorly in the first
half but improved in the second.

00:25:10.182 --> 00:25:12.942
The commentator asked him to explain
his performance in both halves.

00:25:13.110 --> 00:25:17.196
And he said that during halftime,
he heard that someone in the studio

00:25:17.435 --> 00:25:21.635
had criticized him, and that's what
fired him up and made him play better.

00:25:21.812 --> 00:25:25.274
Think about that-he was checking,
verifying, and asking for feedback

00:25:25.424 --> 00:25:28.273
at halftime to see
what people were saying.

00:25:28.370 --> 00:25:30.626
That's how far it's gone,
it's become overwhelming.

00:25:30.814 --> 00:25:33.374
And it's not just hard on the players
but also on the coaches.

00:25:33.543 --> 00:25:36.579
Do you remember when I told you
that you can now find out

00:25:36.729 --> 00:25:39.508
what someone on the other side
of the world, in New Zealand,

00:25:39.635 --> 00:25:42.800
thinks about you? Back in the day,
we just had newspapers...

00:25:42.927 --> 00:25:45.717
You used to wait until the following
day to see what they wrote about you

00:25:45.834 --> 00:25:48.260
in Sport or Slobodna Dalmacija.

00:25:48.488 --> 00:25:53.081
Yes, social media is something else
entirely and can be quite destructive.

00:25:53.334 --> 00:25:56.294
I don't care about it at all,
and I never look at the comments,

00:25:56.700 --> 00:26:00.380
let alone allow anyone
to influence me.

00:26:00.877 --> 00:26:02.663
It's definitely
something very negative.

00:26:02.818 --> 00:26:04.781
Players, however,
are prone to checking it,

00:26:04.942 --> 00:26:07.280
and I had a situation once
with one of my players.

00:26:07.384 --> 00:26:10.390
Entirely by accident, after giving my
halftime speech in the locker room,

00:26:10.505 --> 00:26:12.982
I realized I had forgotten
the stat sheet, so I went back in...

00:26:13.053 --> 00:26:15.068
and there he was, on his phone.

00:26:15.148 --> 00:26:17.086
Honestly, I almost fainted.
I'm not exaggerating.

00:26:17.180 --> 00:26:18.766
After that, I told them,

00:26:18.898 --> 00:26:21.414
"From now on, before the game,
you hand over your phones

00:26:21.558 --> 00:26:24.219
to the team manager, and you won't
get them until after the match."

00:26:24.568 --> 00:26:27.979
You have to fight against it and
try to explain it to them, sadly...

00:26:28.761 --> 00:26:31.823
Look at us-we've been sitting here,
having a great time,

00:26:32.030 --> 00:26:34.310
and neither of us looked at
our phones even once. -Yes, yes.

00:26:34.503 --> 00:26:36.839
That's rare nowadays.
Everyone's glued to their phones

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:41.240
even when you go out with your closest
friends. That's just how it is today.

00:26:41.917 --> 00:26:45.190
Everyone feels entitled to an opinion,
and they often hide behind nicknames.

00:26:45.418 --> 00:26:47.753
Nobody dares to come out
and say something to your face,

00:26:47.875 --> 00:26:50.096
to look you in the eye and
share their thoughts or opinions.

00:26:50.280 --> 00:26:52.280
It's easy to attack
and hate on social media...

00:26:55.168 --> 00:26:57.705
Keyboard warriors-that's what
they call them nowadays. -Exactly.

00:26:57.917 --> 00:27:00.205
And nobody is going to change that.

00:27:00.362 --> 00:27:02.595
In fact, I think it's only
going to get worse. -Yes.

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:05.306
But it'll get worse only for those
who allow it to affect them.

00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:09.500
For those who don't care about it,
they'll continue to live normally.

00:26:52.377 --> 00:26:55.017
I hope to keep living without it,
just like I have until now.

00:27:10.020 --> 00:27:13.940
It doesn't even cross my mind.
I don't use social media platforms,

00:27:14.180 --> 00:27:15.860
and I'm not interested in them.

00:27:16.100 --> 00:27:18.260
My phone is still
just for what's necessary,

00:27:18.500 --> 00:27:21.100
to send and receive messages
and to call someone.

00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:24.300
Nothing can replace the human voice.

00:27:24.580 --> 00:27:30.020
You mentioned earlier
that you've never been fired.

00:27:30.540 --> 00:27:36.380
You know, the legendary Italian coach,
Trapattoni, said 20 years ago

00:27:37.860 --> 00:27:39.860
that there are only coaches
who have been fired

00:27:40.100 --> 00:27:43.180
and those who will be fired.
But that was two decades ago,

00:27:43.325 --> 00:27:45.455
and things have only
gotten worse since then.

00:27:45.606 --> 00:27:49.111
It's not getting any better, is it?
I'm curious about something...

00:27:50.260 --> 00:27:55.860
On one hand, you're the most decorated
coach, and apart from maybe Guardiola,

00:27:56.620 --> 00:28:00.940
you're the only one at this level
who's never been fired.

00:28:01.420 --> 00:28:06.106
From the outside, even as a fan
following your career,

00:28:09.300 --> 00:28:12.140
it looks flawless and perfect.

00:28:13.420 --> 00:28:17.220
Maybe you're not the most qualified
to talk about that side of the job,

00:28:17.500 --> 00:28:21.340
when they start attacking you,
when the rumors start flying,

00:28:21.700 --> 00:28:27.540
when you're questioned, dismissed,
and you begin to doubt yourself...

00:28:28.700 --> 00:28:34.300
But surely, there must have been...
Were there any significant crises?

00:28:34.700 --> 00:28:38.467
I'm not talking about losing games,
that happens, even in finals,

00:28:38.694 --> 00:28:42.752
but were there longer periods
when you felt like you were weakening,

00:28:42.918 --> 00:28:46.174
like your position was in jeopardy...
When was it the hardest for you?

00:28:46.295 --> 00:28:48.471
Who did you turn to
for advice in those moments?

00:28:48.641 --> 00:28:50.642
Do you prefer to be alone,
or with your coaching staff

00:28:50.807 --> 00:28:52.961
or family during those times?

00:28:53.251 --> 00:28:55.891
There was this situation, one year,

00:28:56.114 --> 00:29:00.227
when we played poorly
for several games in a row.

00:29:00.361 --> 00:29:04.055
I told my coaching staff
that I thought that was it,

00:29:04.198 --> 00:29:07.281
that I no longer had
any influence over the players,

00:29:08.376 --> 00:29:10.344
and that we needed to do something.

00:29:10.540 --> 00:29:13.700
And the smartest thing I could think
of at that moment was to resign.

00:29:15.220 --> 00:29:19.740
There was a bit of silence in the
room, and no one said anything.

00:29:20.020 --> 00:29:23.540
I took that as a sign that they agreed
with me, but in reality, they didn't.

00:29:23.740 --> 00:29:28.070
I went to the players and told them,
"Guys, thank you. It's been great,

00:29:29.300 --> 00:29:35.220
but I don't think we can achieve
anything more together. That's it."

00:29:35.540 --> 00:29:39.460
I went home. First, the president
called me to convince me

00:29:39.700 --> 00:29:42.140
it wasn't the right decision.

00:29:42.420 --> 00:29:45.540
Then, people from the club
started calling, and after that,

00:29:45.740 --> 00:29:47.980
all my staff members
reached out to me.

00:29:48.220 --> 00:29:52.100
And then the players started coming
over, begging me not to leave.

00:29:52.340 --> 00:29:53.980
So, I told them,

00:29:54.260 --> 00:29:59.060
"Alright. Do you realize
the situation we're in right now?

00:29:59.620 --> 00:30:04.260
If you want me to stay,
you have to change. You need to...

00:30:04.500 --> 00:30:07.780
We need to do something together to
get out of this difficult moment,

00:30:08.020 --> 00:30:12.460
because there's no point in me staying
if everything stays the same."

00:30:12.940 --> 00:30:15.900
So, I want you to tell me
what I'm doing wrong,

00:30:16.100 --> 00:30:18.349
and feel free to tell me openly,
"Coach, we think this...,"

00:30:18.509 --> 00:30:20.865
and I will also speak openly with you.
Can we do that?

00:30:20.985 --> 00:30:23.068
If we're ready for that,
then let's go.

00:30:23.162 --> 00:30:25.317
We had a meeting, and from that point
on, things started to improve.

00:30:25.407 --> 00:30:27.485
We ended up having
an exceptional season.

00:30:28.265 --> 00:30:30.945
In those moments,
do you like to be alone? -Sorry?

00:30:31.107 --> 00:30:33.035
In those moments,
do you like to be alone?

00:30:33.178 --> 00:30:35.145
People often say, and many
great coaches say it too,

00:30:35.245 --> 00:30:37.254
that a coach is alone in defeat,
when you lose, you're alone.

00:30:37.337 --> 00:30:39.046
Do you like to be alone
during those times?

00:30:39.139 --> 00:30:40.965
Like the legendary
Ćiro Blažević used to say,

00:30:41.033 --> 00:30:43.400
"You lock yourself
in the darkness of your own skin,"

00:30:43.472 --> 00:30:46.232
or do you reach out to your family,
friends, coaching staff...?

00:30:46.485 --> 00:30:49.623
No, I don't reach out.
I'm alone, and I think about it.

00:30:50.201 --> 00:30:54.537
There are always people I trust, and
they always appear at that moment.

00:30:55.361 --> 00:30:57.481
I'm talking to them.

00:30:57.999 --> 00:31:02.412
The decision I made, was a decision
in the interest of the team.

00:31:02.790 --> 00:31:06.214
I had no problem with myself.
It was in the interest of the team.

00:31:06.608 --> 00:31:11.029
It was a club where I worked a lot.
Whether that was saturation or not,

00:31:11.209 --> 00:31:15.998
it later turned out that there wasn’t,
because we achieved results that year as well.

00:31:16.460 --> 00:31:23.631
Obviously, some... Now I could
call it a kind of shock moment.

00:31:24.660 --> 00:31:27.940
Someone has to shock someone.
Did I shock them when I said I was leaving,

00:31:28.220 --> 00:31:31.020
or did they shock me when they said,
"Don't, coach, we believe in you.

00:31:31.260 --> 00:31:34.380
We want you to stay with us."
And then these people from the club.

00:31:34.620 --> 00:31:37.700
That gives you some extra energy
and some motivation.

00:31:37.940 --> 00:31:41.140
That's how it was at that moment.
I really believed at that moment

00:31:41.340 --> 00:31:45.020
that it might be best for me to leave.
Luckily, I had people who believed in me.

00:31:45.300 --> 00:31:48.563
Colleagues and everyone from the club.
It was what it was.

00:31:48.710 --> 00:31:51.085
It's not the end of the world
to make such a decision.

00:31:51.225 --> 00:31:53.531
I don’t think it’s the end of the world
if I get dismissed tomorrow.

00:31:53.662 --> 00:31:55.641
I just wouldn’t want it to
happen at Partizan.

00:31:59.060 --> 00:32:03.460
But, well, as Trapattoni said,
he put it best.

00:32:03.660 --> 00:32:08.100
We depend on this... This is our life.
You move on, that's how it is.

00:32:08.300 --> 00:32:10.420
Someone makes decisions...

00:32:10.580 --> 00:32:14.700
I've always said, you never know,
a tough situation,

00:32:14.900 --> 00:32:17.540
how much it can actually
be good for a person.

00:32:17.740 --> 00:32:20.700
It can help you take the next step.
-When it passes. -When it passes.

00:32:20.900 --> 00:32:23.340
But until it passes...
-Of course, we suffer.

00:32:23.540 --> 00:32:27.860
That’s human nature. -And Guardiola...
Say it. -Yes, yes.

00:32:28.060 --> 00:32:32.340
Even for Guardiola, this will be useful.
Is he comfortable right now? No. -That’s right.

00:32:32.488 --> 00:32:35.008
He has to go through it.
Many fail because of it.

00:32:35.130 --> 00:32:39.290
Maybe if Guardiola weren’t Guardiola, he would
have probably been sacked at some point.

00:32:39.435 --> 00:32:42.562
But Guardiola has built...
You can only do this...

00:32:42.745 --> 00:32:47.865
Bravo, maestro, and that’s it.
-How do you handle defeat?

00:32:48.340 --> 00:32:51.604
Conte once said a phenomenal sentence.

00:32:51.824 --> 00:32:54.904
The problem in this job is that
you don’t enjoy victory

00:32:55.119 --> 00:33:00.698
as much as you suffer in defeat.
-Yes. I have to tell you one thing.

00:33:00.965 --> 00:33:05.299
If you ever decide not to go into coaching,
you’d be phenomenal at this.

00:33:05.495 --> 00:33:10.415
You're an encyclopedia.
-No, no. -I’m serious. Unbelievable.

00:33:11.050 --> 00:33:15.955
You’ve already quoted so many people.
Yes, defeat is something nobody likes.

00:33:16.147 --> 00:33:19.080
But it's necessary. -When we talk
among ourselves, coaches,

00:33:19.182 --> 00:33:21.416
we say what a beautiful day it is.
The morning when you wake up after a win.

00:33:21.534 --> 00:33:22.974
There’s no better day.

00:33:23.080 --> 00:33:29.703
When I became the coach of Partizan,
I lost two games in the season, in our league.

00:33:29.867 --> 00:33:33.726
The first was against Bosna from Sarajevo,
after overtime, and one against Rabotnički.

00:33:33.863 --> 00:33:36.495
When we lost to Rabotnički,
I didn’t leave the house for seven days.

00:33:36.583 --> 00:33:40.263
I thought anyone walking down the street
was pointing at me and saying,

00:33:40.377 --> 00:33:42.017
"Look at this fool."

00:33:42.133 --> 00:33:45.231
I really thought that.
-That’s the responsibility.

00:33:45.420 --> 00:33:48.380
But now, when I lose a game,
you lost a game, and you move on.

00:33:48.580 --> 00:33:52.420
I don’t even dwell on it. I told you,
back then in the locker room,

00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:56.380
right after the game, I would do
an analysis, talk for 5, 10, 15 minutes.

00:33:56.580 --> 00:34:00.260
Now: "Guys, training is tomorrow
or the day after. Bye."

00:34:00.700 --> 00:34:03.780
That’s the only way. You can’t
win everything, it’s impossible.

00:34:03.980 --> 00:34:06.420
You have to lose sometimes.
Of course, it’s better when you win.

00:34:06.700 --> 00:34:10.180
You’re happier, more satisfied.
Everyone is happy, and the atmosphere

00:34:10.420 --> 00:34:13.540
after a win is incredible. There’s
probably nothing better. -That’s it.

00:34:13.740 --> 00:34:19.980
Everyone is like brothers, sisters,
friends. -Yes, there’s no feeling like it.

00:34:20.340 --> 00:34:21.860
Tell me...

00:34:22.940 --> 00:34:26.180
You're very proud of your relationship
with former players.

00:34:27.140 --> 00:34:32.980
What do you tell them when
they ask for advice after retiring?

00:34:33.700 --> 00:34:40.620
Should they go into... Should they
become coaches or do something else?

00:34:41.060 --> 00:34:45.100
What’s your advice?
They definitely ask you. -Yes.

00:34:46.340 --> 00:34:49.460
Life after a playing career
is just beginning.

00:34:49.660 --> 00:34:53.940
I tell them life is waiting for them,
and they should choose to do what they love.

00:34:54.140 --> 00:34:57.820
The dilemma is always whether to be
a president, sports director, or coach.

00:34:58.020 --> 00:35:00.260
Should I open a café,
a restaurant, etc.?

00:35:00.460 --> 00:35:03.420
Do what you think you should do,
what you love to do. That’s number one.

00:35:03.660 --> 00:35:06.900
Number two, I was lucky that...
Until a few years ago,

00:35:07.060 --> 00:35:11.740
there were over 100, now I don’t know,
players I coached who are now coaches.

00:35:11.940 --> 00:35:17.780
At various levels. Some were even
in ministries, presidents of federations.

00:35:18.020 --> 00:35:21.100
Dejan Bodiroga is now
the president of the EuroLeague.

00:35:21.700 --> 00:35:25.460
Successful people. There were
some who didn’t quite find their way.

00:35:25.980 --> 00:35:30.020
Some strayed and went into
completely different fields,

00:35:30.300 --> 00:35:33.460
though I don’t understand why,
but that’s their right.

00:35:34.100 --> 00:35:38.180
I was always open to them
and always told them what I thought

00:35:38.380 --> 00:35:43.500
was good for them, but I always said,
and I’ll say it again, do what you love to do.

00:35:43.820 --> 00:35:49.140
Don’t wake up one morning with
the idea that you want to be a coach...

00:35:49.420 --> 00:35:55.580
A great player, a really great player,
asked me a few years ago:

00:35:56.220 --> 00:35:58.980
"Žoc..." That’s my nickname.

00:35:59.220 --> 00:36:02.900
"I want to be a coach, but do I really
have to be at every training session?"

00:36:03.300 --> 00:36:07.140
I told him, don’t get into this job.

00:36:08.540 --> 00:36:10.780
What am I trying to say?
You wake up thinking,

00:36:10.980 --> 00:36:14.020
"I want to be this," and the next day,
"I want to be this, I want to be that."

00:36:14.220 --> 00:36:16.940
If you’re lost and don’t have a clear idea,
there’s nothing worse than that.

00:36:17.140 --> 00:36:18.820
Do something else.

00:36:19.020 --> 00:36:23.580
Life is incredible, you can find
yourself where you’re meant to be.

00:36:24.780 --> 00:36:27.460
I understand 100%.
-Be dedicated.

00:36:27.700 --> 00:36:34.160
I’m at that age when players retire,
and I tell them that professional sports,

00:36:34.500 --> 00:36:38.300
especially those that bring money,
football, basketball, and other sports...

00:36:39.100 --> 00:36:42.060
There are many roles
that can fulfill you.

00:36:42.460 --> 00:36:46.420
They are well paid,
but being important matters.

00:36:46.700 --> 00:36:50.060
The most important thing for a player
is to stay relevant.

00:36:50.260 --> 00:36:52.580
He wants to be important,
like everyone else.

00:36:52.820 --> 00:36:58.780
You can be a director, an advisor,
a chief scout-there are many roles.

00:36:59.140 --> 00:37:05.540
I tell them, when you’re a director,
you’re just a token, like in pinball.

00:37:05.740 --> 00:37:07.860
And coaches are the balls.

00:37:08.220 --> 00:37:12.380
As a director, you have three lives,
three coaches you can replace.

00:37:12.620 --> 00:37:14.420
That’s one downside.

00:37:16.100 --> 00:37:19.260
For example, I never in my life,
though I had offers,

00:37:19.437 --> 00:37:21.397
wanted to be anything else.

00:37:21.740 --> 00:37:26.860
I always told everyone, the only thing
I want and love to do is to be a coach.

00:37:27.100 --> 00:37:30.460
The court. I can’t see
myself as a club president,

00:37:30.660 --> 00:37:35.940
a sports director, or anything else
in life. I can only be a coach.

00:37:36.180 --> 00:37:40.900
Everything else I love to do, in my
free time, is my right, and I will do it.

00:37:41.350 --> 00:37:44.081
But that’s not a profession.
We’re talking about this.

00:37:44.239 --> 00:37:46.558
I’m just a coach,
focused on this.

00:37:46.767 --> 00:37:50.011
Maybe I could do something else, but
I’m not going to test myself at this age.

00:37:50.145 --> 00:37:53.230
It doesn’t even cross my mind.
This is more than enough for me.

00:37:53.371 --> 00:37:57.363
I know how I do my job.
I’m at peace with myself.

00:37:57.654 --> 00:38:03.614
Now, what you said was nice. Players
have their whole lives ahead of them,

00:38:03.759 --> 00:38:06.399
sometimes they struggle
and need help.

00:38:06.553 --> 00:38:09.313
Everyone who came to me
and asked for my opinion,

00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:12.542
I always tried to help and I will help.
These are people I love.

00:38:12.780 --> 00:38:16.740
I can’t forget those moments
when I lived with someone for ten years

00:38:16.940 --> 00:38:21.326
and now suddenly they don’t matter.
-Absolutely...

00:38:22.740 --> 00:38:25.340
Do you know why
you can’t be something else?

00:38:27.260 --> 00:38:31.420
That’s what I tell the players.
If you start being a coach, it’s over.

00:38:31.660 --> 00:38:35.180
There’s no turning back.
It takes you in completely. Why?

00:38:35.620 --> 00:38:39.100
Because, in essence,
it’s the only real thing.

00:38:39.420 --> 00:38:42.380
It’s the only place
where you feel adrenaline,

00:38:45.260 --> 00:38:47.260
responsibility, and everything else.

00:38:47.460 --> 00:38:51.540
Yes, but there are players who
understand what that job means,

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:55.100
and who say, "I could never do this."
-True. -That’s respect.

00:38:55.300 --> 00:39:00.220
And then you have the others, who live
for it, and while they are players...

00:39:00.820 --> 00:39:04.860
From every generation, I could point out
who could become a coach.

00:39:05.100 --> 00:39:09.580
The players I coached.
I told Jasikevičius many years ago

00:39:09.820 --> 00:39:12.220
that he would be a coach
one day. Of course.

00:39:12.311 --> 00:39:14.631
Just like I told all the others. I could
exactly tell from each generation,

00:39:14.766 --> 00:39:17.841
"You will be a coach one day."
Now, from this Partizan team,

00:39:17.981 --> 00:39:20.021
I can name precisely
who will become a coach.

00:39:20.168 --> 00:39:22.968
I can write it down, that’s
what I’ll do, it would be great,

00:39:23.137 --> 00:39:25.403
to bet on who will become a coach.

00:39:27.700 --> 00:39:31.100
Did you just beat Spanoulis? -Yes.

00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:35.140
Fascinating.

00:39:36.020 --> 00:39:37.660
You said...

00:39:38.220 --> 00:39:43.700
If you sat on the bench,
it wouldn’t make sense, right?

00:39:44.515 --> 00:39:48.820
If I did? -If you sat on the bench,
instead of standing during the game,

00:39:49.100 --> 00:39:51.851
it wouldn’t be the same,
it wouldn’t make sense.

00:39:52.143 --> 00:39:55.640
That’s the passion of these
greats who simply...

00:39:55.956 --> 00:40:00.956
have to be there, on the sideline,
and at the same time, it’s madness.

00:40:01.143 --> 00:40:06.203
I’m talking about your completeness.
At the same time, you highlight

00:40:06.444 --> 00:40:13.680
your absolute focus on the game
as your greatest quality. -Yes.

00:40:14.940 --> 00:40:16.540
I know that.

00:40:18.260 --> 00:40:20.740
Whenever I have...

00:40:22.900 --> 00:40:27.180
looked or look strange,
I know the level of focus I have.

00:40:30.940 --> 00:40:33.780
And how necessary that is
to lead the game the right way

00:40:34.020 --> 00:40:38.940
and to be able to help your team.
I tune everything out.

00:40:39.140 --> 00:40:42.660
Everything that happens in the arena,
many times, I truly don’t hear it.

00:40:42.860 --> 00:40:46.060
I don’t hear the cheering or the noise.
If we’re playing away,

00:40:46.300 --> 00:40:48.700
and someone is
calling me out. No.

00:40:48.940 --> 00:40:53.740
I always told my players
when they take free throws...

00:40:53.940 --> 00:40:57.980
Focus. Concentrate.
If you can hear the ball hitting the floor,

00:40:58.220 --> 00:41:02.140
but not the people on the sides,
not even when they whistle at you.

00:41:02.380 --> 00:41:09.580
I managed to train myself for that,
and I think that’s the most important thing.

00:41:09.820 --> 00:41:14.860
Earlier, we talked about how much
a coach can influence a basketball game.

00:41:15.740 --> 00:41:20.300
On the other hand,
when I sit on the bench,

00:41:20.780 --> 00:41:23.940
I ask my assistants to talk.

00:41:24.740 --> 00:41:29.100
Those were famous scenes when
I worked at Panathinaikos-Dimitris,

00:41:29.780 --> 00:41:35.420
who became a great coach, and I.
The referees would come to calm us down,

00:41:35.700 --> 00:41:39.300
because they thought we had a problem,
that we were about to fight.

00:41:39.540 --> 00:41:43.020
I told him, "Dimče, talk."

00:41:43.540 --> 00:41:46.260
"I’m going to say the worst
things to you during the game,

00:41:46.500 --> 00:41:49.340
but I will listen to you."
And I did listen to him.

00:41:49.580 --> 00:41:53.740
I did what he told me to do,
but I insulted him.

00:41:54.100 --> 00:41:56.820
That still happens to me today,
not just with one assistant.

00:41:57.300 --> 00:42:01.060
I’ve said that not only are they
valuable to me,

00:42:01.300 --> 00:42:06.220
they help me so much that I think
without assistant coaches, I’d be nothing.

00:42:06.460 --> 00:42:08.700
I truly believe that. -True.

00:42:08.940 --> 00:42:13.340
Just like I believe
that a basketball club

00:42:13.540 --> 00:42:18.140
can’t function without physiotherapists,
equipment managers, doctors.

00:42:18.380 --> 00:42:21.540
All those supporting staff
who take care of the players.

00:42:21.671 --> 00:42:24.471
I’ve always said,
when I observe my players,

00:42:24.623 --> 00:42:26.903
I pay much more attention
to how they treat

00:42:27.026 --> 00:42:29.052
the equipment manager
and the physiotherapist

00:42:29.158 --> 00:42:31.294
than how they treat me.
They always behave nicely toward me.

00:42:31.445 --> 00:42:33.965
They know I’m the boss
and that they depend on me.

00:42:34.080 --> 00:42:36.040
Of course. -But I watch
how they act.

00:42:36.208 --> 00:42:37.998
That shows me what
kind of people they are.

00:42:38.199 --> 00:42:42.312
If you're a good person with me,
you can have a bad game,

00:42:42.515 --> 00:42:45.469
you can make mistakes,
but I will understand.

00:42:45.707 --> 00:42:50.107
If you’re not... well,
it’s going to be tough.

00:42:50.580 --> 00:42:55.140
Do you feel that players today
lack individuality on the court?

00:42:56.644 --> 00:42:57.879
Tell me...

00:42:59.180 --> 00:43:02.942
This year, there was a moment
when one player "exploded,"

00:43:03.300 --> 00:43:07.180
and when I took him out to calm him down,
he told me, "Let me be myself."

00:43:08.180 --> 00:43:12.180
Of course! You need to be yourself.
But I can’t allow you

00:43:12.420 --> 00:43:17.180
to put the team in a situation
where you get another technical foul

00:43:17.420 --> 00:43:21.580
and get kicked out. Do you understand
why I subbed you out? -Yes, yes.

00:43:21.820 --> 00:43:25.366
Be yourself, you should be yourself,
it’s best when you’re you.

00:43:26.053 --> 00:43:32.374
Basically, you’re saying-your completeness,
we play defense this way, that’s it.

00:43:32.530 --> 00:43:35.488
I’ll draw up the offense for you, and now
you think everything is planned out.

00:43:35.860 --> 00:43:38.900
But then you say, "I’d love for you
to surprise me with something."

00:43:39.140 --> 00:43:45.376
Give me something of your own!
That’s becoming less common today.

00:43:46.064 --> 00:43:53.673
In football, dribbling is becoming rarer.
-Smart players-when there’s a time-out,

00:43:54.140 --> 00:43:57.227
I draw up a play,
and on the first possession,

00:43:57.387 --> 00:44:00.126
he does something completely different.

00:44:00.909 --> 00:44:05.869
Of course, we miss-or rather,
he misses. Bad decision.

00:44:06.178 --> 00:44:09.110
On the second possession,
he does exactly what I drew up,

00:44:09.220 --> 00:44:12.055
and the player gets a wide-open shot.
He missed, but he was wide open.

00:44:12.155 --> 00:44:14.899
After the game, I ask him,
"Do you remember what I said?" "Yes."

00:44:15.089 --> 00:44:17.609
"Why?" "I was reading the defense."
That’s basketball.

00:44:17.808 --> 00:44:21.985
I tell him, "Of course."
"Why did you follow the second play?"

00:44:22.134 --> 00:44:25.237
"Was he open?" "Yes."
"Why don’t you trust me?

00:44:25.401 --> 00:44:28.751
Do you not trust me?"
"I trust you, coach." "Then do it."

00:44:28.967 --> 00:44:32.287
When the game is "alive,"
when you're running up and down,

00:44:32.425 --> 00:44:34.682
then you can "read"
and do whatever you want.

00:44:34.829 --> 00:44:37.370
I’m happiest when
a player surprises me.

00:44:37.542 --> 00:44:40.136
That rarely happens.
When a player surprises me,

00:44:40.243 --> 00:44:42.511
I’m the happiest person in the world.

00:44:42.668 --> 00:44:45.604
Yes, when he surprises
you outside the system,

00:44:45.766 --> 00:44:48.934
then that improvisation is amazing.
The most beautiful thing.

00:44:49.071 --> 00:44:51.293
But if it’s only improvisation,
then it’s chaos. -That’s right.

00:44:51.491 --> 00:44:54.171
Isn’t that so? -Yes, it is.
-That’s the fine line. -Exactly.

00:44:54.620 --> 00:45:00.900
Has your ego ever held you back,
or does it hold you back at all

00:45:02.100 --> 00:45:04.260
when it comes to your NBA story?

00:45:04.500 --> 00:45:07.700
I read that you mentioned
a few times that they called you

00:45:07.940 --> 00:45:12.980
for interviews and all that.
Of course, it seems illogical to you.

00:45:13.220 --> 00:45:17.540
How can that be explained,
that it hasn’t happened-not to you,

00:45:17.740 --> 00:45:23.100
nor to these other coaches...
But to you, for example.

00:45:23.860 --> 00:45:27.500
I don’t know. Honestly,
I’ve never been in a situation

00:45:27.740 --> 00:45:30.580
where someone seriously
talked to me about it.

00:45:30.820 --> 00:45:33.420
There was that one time when
they called me for an interview,

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:38.919
and I jokingly said
that interviews are for journalists.

00:45:39.372 --> 00:45:41.763
They all know who I am, etc.

00:45:42.100 --> 00:45:46.580
That whole story about adaptation...
I think that any coach in Europe

00:45:46.820 --> 00:45:51.100
who is at a certain EuroLeague level
can also coach in the NBA.

00:45:51.340 --> 00:45:54.140
It’s just a matter of those people
giving you their trust.

00:45:54.340 --> 00:45:57.540
We all understand and know
how relationships are built.

00:45:57.780 --> 00:45:59.900
You’ve moved from
one level to another.

00:46:00.140 --> 00:46:03.580
Of course, the NBA is a bit different,
but it’s not that different.

00:46:05.140 --> 00:46:08.380
Joe Dumars had a saying,
he said that basketball is universal.

00:46:08.580 --> 00:46:11.580
Basketball is the same everywhere.
So, well...

00:46:11.932 --> 00:46:14.049
So, I didn’t have any offers,
so I didn’t rush anywhere.

00:46:14.102 --> 00:46:15.902
I’m very happy here.

00:46:16.980 --> 00:46:21.500
Europe was my destination,
starting from Badalona, Madrid,

00:46:21.980 --> 00:46:26.180
Treviso, Athens, Istanbul.

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:30.700
Now I’ve returned here home,
after 28 years.

00:46:31.020 --> 00:46:34.780
My happiness knows no bounds.
I’m living the life I love.

00:46:34.980 --> 00:46:37.620
I’m surrounded by people
who respect me,

00:46:37.860 --> 00:46:40.140
and on top of all that,
I have love.

00:46:40.340 --> 00:46:42.940
I always say that I have enough love
and that there are people

00:46:43.180 --> 00:46:45.140
who surely love me.
And this is something special.

00:46:45.380 --> 00:46:48.940
Wherever I worked, I was
highly respected and loved.

00:46:50.020 --> 00:46:54.260
Because of that, there was no need
for me, to run or hurry anywhere.

00:46:54.460 --> 00:46:57.580
I didn’t have an ego that would
push me to prove myself.

00:46:57.820 --> 00:47:01.660
Many people from the NBA
who were, or are now coaches,

00:47:01.860 --> 00:47:05.140
came to my practices.
They are my friends.

00:47:05.380 --> 00:47:07.900
They took from me,
and I took from them.

00:47:08.100 --> 00:47:14.020
In this modern era, you click and see
that everyone is copying each other...

00:47:15.180 --> 00:47:17.060
Click and you watch Guardiola...

00:47:17.260 --> 00:47:19.380
This one isn’t good,
he has long passes, etc.

00:47:19.620 --> 00:47:21.580
These are all told stories.

00:47:22.660 --> 00:47:25.060
I was satisfied with myself
right where I was,

00:47:25.206 --> 00:47:26.966
and to this day, I’m very satisfied.

00:47:27.152 --> 00:47:29.752
And I’m very happy.
Even at this moment.

00:47:29.984 --> 00:47:33.824
This specific conversation
makes me very happy. -Thank you.

00:47:34.025 --> 00:47:36.385
Thank you for this wonderful
conversation we’re having.

00:47:36.540 --> 00:47:38.300
But we have to ask you this,

00:47:38.447 --> 00:47:40.687
even though it's not the topic
of the show, it’s relevant.

00:47:40.889 --> 00:47:43.009
I have to ask you since we’ve
already mentioned the NBA.

00:47:43.217 --> 00:47:46.043
Can you comment on the decision
that is currently relevant,

00:47:46.197 --> 00:47:49.077
and is related to Dončić?
How do you see it?

00:47:49.980 --> 00:47:55.540
All those who are there and who understand
it much more than I do, are surprised.

00:47:56.740 --> 00:48:00.540
It has once again shown that all the players
have commented that it's a business.

00:48:00.740 --> 00:48:04.060
At the end of the day,
there is no sentimentality, no love.

00:48:04.300 --> 00:48:06.860
If five days before it happened,
someone had mentioned

00:48:07.100 --> 00:48:09.940
something like that, they would probably
have said that he’s crazy,

00:48:10.089 --> 00:48:11.769
that he’s a patient for psychiatry.

00:48:11.868 --> 00:48:13.708
They would have said
that something like that

00:48:13.822 --> 00:48:15.382
couldn’t happen, but it happened.

00:48:15.474 --> 00:48:19.003
What the interests are,
how, and why, time will show.

00:48:19.254 --> 00:48:22.414
Whether that Dallas manager
was right or not, who knows,

00:48:22.718 --> 00:48:27.998
but some new players in Dallas
will definitely get an opportunity.

00:48:28.620 --> 00:48:31.420
Luka will get the opportunity
to show his incredible talent

00:48:31.820 --> 00:48:34.580
and everything he offers in the Lakers.

00:48:35.060 --> 00:48:37.020
I don’t know how it will look,
but that’s how it is.

00:48:38.620 --> 00:48:41.980
But again, I say, it’s a business.
-Yes. -Business above all.

00:48:42.220 --> 00:48:45.260
That’s why the NBA
is the best league.

00:48:45.500 --> 00:48:48.460
I had the opportunity to spend
just over a month in Detroit.

00:48:48.660 --> 00:48:51.820
That organization is a miracle.
It’s something incredible.

00:48:51.950 --> 00:48:54.430
They definitely pay attention
to everything.

00:48:54.604 --> 00:48:57.172
To everything, down to
the smallest detail.

00:48:57.848 --> 00:49:01.208
If we in EuroLeague,
at this level of competition,

00:49:01.455 --> 00:49:05.984
made every game important,
the viewership would grow even more.

00:49:06.230 --> 00:49:08.750
Even the Americans
have started broadcasting it.

00:49:08.966 --> 00:49:13.531
If we took some things from them,
it would be phenomenal.

00:49:15.900 --> 00:49:18.500
You said: "First, you need
to remain a person."

00:49:20.780 --> 00:49:23.980
And: "For Partizan, I’ll give
everything except my dignity."

00:49:24.820 --> 00:49:29.060
You were 13 years in Greece,
7 years in Turkey...

00:49:29.260 --> 00:49:32.300
I was also in Turkey. Phenomenal
people, phenomenal country...

00:49:32.500 --> 00:49:36.740
You were in a giant. -Yes.
I was there for 2 years.

00:49:39.140 --> 00:49:46.410
Let’s ignore the 13 years in Greece,
but staying 7 years at Fenerbahçe

00:49:47.800 --> 00:49:52.202
you can't do if you’re just a good coach.
They had many coaches.

00:49:52.436 --> 00:49:55.897
Zico was there too, he won
the championship, but he had to leave.

00:49:56.077 --> 00:50:02.161
My neighbor was Aziz Yildirim.
He fires the coach at halftime.

00:50:03.072 --> 00:50:06.013
You didn’t win all seven titles. -Yes.

00:50:06.724 --> 00:50:11.060
How do you explain that?
Do you feel special

00:50:11.334 --> 00:50:15.560
because of the fact that people
respect you, appreciate you,

00:50:15.796 --> 00:50:18.236
love you, wherever you go?

00:50:19.399 --> 00:50:23.084
It turned out to be that way.
I am proud of that fact.

00:50:23.376 --> 00:50:30.255
The person you mentioned,
Aziz Yildirim, after my first contract,

00:50:30.420 --> 00:50:36.060
insisted that we extend the cooperation
and sign a five-year contract.

00:50:36.300 --> 00:50:40.900
I was cautious because I realized
that it was a huge period.

00:50:40.999 --> 00:50:42.674
I said: "Let’s not tie ourselves
down that much,

00:50:42.789 --> 00:50:44.455
let’s sign something more realistic."

00:50:44.551 --> 00:50:46.721
In the end, we agreed that
it would be a three-year contract.

00:50:46.830 --> 00:50:49.487
He insisted a lot.
He’s a wonderful person.

00:50:49.604 --> 00:50:52.252
The relationship I had with him
was incredible.

00:50:52.354 --> 00:50:54.682
Even today, when I go to Istanbul,
I meet with him,

00:50:54.748 --> 00:50:57.025
despite the fact that he has
a small problem with communication

00:50:57.132 --> 00:50:58.807
because of the language... - Yes.

00:50:59.043 --> 00:51:02.059
He is a wonderful person, and we
understood each other very well,

00:51:02.901 --> 00:51:07.181
despite everything. What else
can I say, except that I am proud,

00:51:07.340 --> 00:51:11.620
happy, and satisfied with the fact
that people recognized my dedication.

00:51:11.860 --> 00:51:16.068
I think that’s the most important thing.
Also, they recognized what I built.

00:51:16.225 --> 00:51:18.481
Because, during my time there,
basketball gained significance.

00:51:18.601 --> 00:51:21.844
There is a statistic on how many
children in 2017. followed

00:51:21.990 --> 00:51:24.810
that final game on various
squares in Turkey.

00:51:26.300 --> 00:51:29.180
This led to the creation
of new generations of fans

00:51:29.380 --> 00:51:31.420
of Fenerbahçe and
basketball in general.

00:51:31.620 --> 00:51:36.580
After that, Efes won two titles.
Then there’s also Partizan.

00:51:36.860 --> 00:51:42.740
I’m especially proud of the fact
that we have new generations of fans.

00:51:43.100 --> 00:51:44.946
There are many kids,
kids who enjoy it.

00:51:45.033 --> 00:51:48.019
Those are your clubs. -Excuse me?
-Those are your clubs, sorry.

00:51:48.108 --> 00:51:49.748
I’m talking about Zadar.

00:51:49.934 --> 00:51:54.347
An example is the ABA League
in this region.

00:51:56.260 --> 00:52:00.061
Zagreb, Split, Zadar...
Split is a demanding city.

00:52:00.186 --> 00:52:02.279
Zadar, we’ve already
talked about that. - Yes.

00:52:02.492 --> 00:52:06.311
Some will say,
Zadar is a basketball city.

00:52:06.465 --> 00:52:09.625
Yes, it’s a basketball city,
but it’s also a city

00:52:09.818 --> 00:52:14.679
that suffered a lot in the war
along with several other cities.

00:52:14.905 --> 00:52:18.827
And the people haven’t forgotten that,
because it wasn’t that long ago.

00:52:19.163 --> 00:52:22.093
Despite that, the people in Zadar
welcome you like that,

00:52:22.273 --> 00:52:24.565
even if you're not
the Zadar coach. -Yes.

00:52:26.782 --> 00:52:34.100
Personally, I think people know
coach Željko Obradović

00:52:34.500 --> 00:52:36.260
and some of my results.

00:52:36.860 --> 00:52:40.580
But what you mentioned earlier,
honor, honesty,

00:52:40.860 --> 00:52:45.140
and some of the views I have,
I assume that’s what led to people

00:52:45.340 --> 00:52:48.500
treating me like that
in Split, Zadar, and Zagreb.

00:52:48.980 --> 00:52:51.740
I’ve always been myself,
and I will always be.

00:52:51.980 --> 00:52:54.460
I’ve always said what I think.

00:52:54.740 --> 00:52:59.940
I’ve never stepped onto courts
where I thought I wasn’t ready.

00:53:01.380 --> 00:53:08.612
I believe that we only, by chance,
were born here or there.

00:53:08.708 --> 00:53:10.701
We are, above all, people.

00:53:10.845 --> 00:53:13.230
And if we are good people,
then we understand each other.

00:53:13.355 --> 00:53:15.362
The best understanding
is between good people,

00:53:15.509 --> 00:53:18.644
and the whole essence is in that.
I have many friends.

00:53:18.855 --> 00:53:23.019
Life has taken me,
I repeat, from Spain,

00:53:23.231 --> 00:53:25.917
through Italy, Greece, Turkey...

00:53:26.960 --> 00:53:29.720
The friendships I have made
are unforgettable and there are

00:53:30.140 --> 00:53:34.420
always good and bad people,
in every city, in every village.

00:53:35.300 --> 00:53:40.780
I returned to Čačak, to the street
where I have lived since 1965.,

00:53:41.020 --> 00:53:44.980
where my late father built a house.
Across from that house lives a man

00:53:45.134 --> 00:53:48.286
whose friend I have been since
that year and who is my godfather.

00:53:48.465 --> 00:53:50.585
They are all still mine.

00:53:50.739 --> 00:53:54.259
About thirty of them
received seasonal tickets

00:53:54.507 --> 00:53:57.907
for Partizan’n matches
as a gift from me. All of them.

00:53:58.273 --> 00:54:01.755
Because, I'm sure,
if they were in my situation,

00:54:01.905 --> 00:54:04.629
they would do the same. That's it.

00:54:05.209 --> 00:54:07.239
You were born somewhere,
you lived with those people

00:54:07.351 --> 00:54:09.031
and today you love them.

00:54:09.159 --> 00:54:12.075
Life took you somewhere else
where you also have friends.

00:54:12.291 --> 00:54:14.419
Aziz Yildirim,
a friend for life. -Yes.

00:54:14.600 --> 00:54:18.160
I won’t list all the cities
where I have worked.

00:54:18.991 --> 00:54:27.311
I mentionede to you the celebration
of my fiftiet birthday with 850 guests.

00:54:27.550 --> 00:54:31.030
Guests from all over Europe
were invited and they all came.

00:54:31.114 --> 00:54:33.326
I did something that was
of a humanitarian character

00:54:33.420 --> 00:54:35.340
and I will never be able
to forget that.

00:54:35.773 --> 00:54:40.333
That is exactly the greatest wealth
that a person can have. -Well done!

00:54:40.700 --> 00:54:43.580
And after 28 years,
as you said earlier,

00:54:43.780 --> 00:54:46.660
you’re coming back home
and saying: "I’m flying."

00:54:46.860 --> 00:54:51.100
I’m in my city, doing what I love,
but at home. -Yes.

00:54:51.780 --> 00:54:53.860
This conversation that
you and I are having,

00:54:54.006 --> 00:54:56.326
hopefully shows you how much
I love talking about basketball.

00:54:56.519 --> 00:54:58.439
I’m here in Belgrade.

00:54:58.577 --> 00:55:03.219
At one point, it happened,
thanks to Zoran Savić,

00:55:03.446 --> 00:55:05.646
who was the club director
and president Ostoja Mijajlović

00:55:05.798 --> 00:55:07.758
and their persistence.

00:55:07.906 --> 00:55:10.211
For a year, they kept calling me,
but in the end,

00:55:10.500 --> 00:55:15.260
I had a conversation with myself
and said: "Now or never."

00:55:15.500 --> 00:55:19.140
That "now" was phenomenal
and I feel that way now.

00:55:19.340 --> 00:55:23.100
We’re living a fairytale with Partizan,
because the goal we have ahead of us

00:55:23.237 --> 00:55:26.197
is for Partizan to be a permanent
member of the EuroLeague.

00:55:26.397 --> 00:55:28.837
That is our most important goal
and we are working on it.

00:55:29.029 --> 00:55:31.309
If someone had told me
that it would look like this

00:55:31.431 --> 00:55:33.791
when I agreed to coach Partizan
and that we would have by far

00:55:33.958 --> 00:55:38.050
the largest viewership,
I would have said it’s impossible.

00:55:38.290 --> 00:55:40.238
But, it happened that way.

00:55:40.411 --> 00:55:43.777
Once again, I will mention that loyalty
which the Partizan fans show us

00:55:44.013 --> 00:55:46.413
in the toughest moments.
It’s something incredible.

00:55:46.980 --> 00:55:50.460
I truly don’t have the words
to express my gratitude to them.

00:55:51.020 --> 00:55:55.820
They especially welcome me,
and I insist that they help the players

00:55:56.140 --> 00:56:00.980
and I ask them, and I will keep asking
them for that, but that love is rare.

00:56:01.220 --> 00:56:05.020
I truly, sincerely believe that
Partizan is a very specific club.

00:56:05.232 --> 00:56:07.472
A club like that doesn’t exist
anywhere else.

00:56:09.380 --> 00:56:12.580
You can tell, when you
talk about Partizan,

00:56:12.887 --> 00:56:14.890
it’s like you’re flying,
just like you said.

00:56:15.115 --> 00:56:16.583
And tell me this...

00:56:16.819 --> 00:56:19.164
You’re very social
and have many friends.

00:56:19.316 --> 00:56:21.469
And that birthday,
although not just that...

00:56:21.629 --> 00:56:24.515
But, what’s the situation with hobbies?
There’s also your family...

00:56:24.781 --> 00:56:29.273
Food, wine, music, movies,
what are your hobbies?

00:56:30.469 --> 00:56:32.406
I have many hobbies.

00:56:32.633 --> 00:56:39.020
When I get on a plane...
Book. I read a lot.

00:56:39.780 --> 00:56:42.660
And another type of relaxation
is crossword puzzles.

00:56:42.900 --> 00:56:47.060
Often, when I lie down in bed,
if I'm not really sleepy,

00:56:47.300 --> 00:56:50.700
if I’m not watching a video,
I do a crossword puzzle or a book.

00:56:51.420 --> 00:56:56.460
I love to read and I read a lot.
-What do you read? - I read everything.

00:56:56.895 --> 00:57:02.415
First of all, I read Serbian writers,
but since I speak Spanish,

00:57:02.530 --> 00:57:06.350
Italian, and English, I can read
in those languages as well.

00:57:06.463 --> 00:57:09.068
Of course, to perfect those languages,
I read literature in those.

00:57:09.224 --> 00:57:11.464
For example, I read a lot
of literature in Spanish.

00:57:12.313 --> 00:57:16.522
Of course, there are hit makers,
you can distinguish true literature

00:57:16.815 --> 00:57:19.535
from relaxing literature, etc.

00:57:20.660 --> 00:57:25.420
That’s one thing, the other thing is,
as you said, company.

00:57:25.660 --> 00:57:27.740
Yes, I really love
spending time with people.

00:57:27.886 --> 00:57:30.166
Music is, I personally think,

00:57:30.375 --> 00:57:33.596
something that is the most
important in people’s lives.

00:57:33.777 --> 00:57:36.817
Without music, life would be
so boring, so different...

00:57:37.127 --> 00:57:40.727
When you get in the car in
the morning and turn on the radio,

00:57:40.904 --> 00:57:42.984
the music immediately wakes you up.

00:57:43.146 --> 00:57:46.026
Music always cheers me up
and I love all kinds of music.

00:57:46.188 --> 00:57:49.188
I enjoy music.
Earlier, when I had time,

00:57:49.373 --> 00:57:53.346
I loved going fishing. Unfortunately,
now I don’t have the time, but once,

00:57:54.820 --> 00:58:01.980
thanks to a friend in Barcelona,
I went on a "real" fishing trip.

00:58:02.220 --> 00:58:05.300
We were fishing for tuna,
and it was something incredible.

00:58:05.413 --> 00:58:07.582
I hope that one day,
when I finish my career

00:58:07.660 --> 00:58:09.540
and have more time,
I will be able to do that.

00:58:09.688 --> 00:58:11.848
There are some parts of the world,
and also parts of my

00:58:12.024 --> 00:58:15.356
beautiful country, Serbia,
that I haven’t managed to visit,

00:58:15.472 --> 00:58:17.992
but I will definitely visit
and I will do so with my best friend.

00:58:18.168 --> 00:58:20.008
That’s what awaits me.

00:58:20.139 --> 00:58:22.499
You know, I’m very young,
so I have time.

00:58:23.361 --> 00:58:25.121
All of that is ahead of me.

00:58:25.323 --> 00:58:30.684
What does Serbia have in basketball
that Croatia doesn’t have?

00:58:31.010 --> 00:58:33.970
Or, what does Croatia have
in football that Serbia doesn’t have?

00:58:34.186 --> 00:58:37.535
Is it passion, is it
quality, responsibility,

00:58:37.942 --> 00:58:41.620
or the quality of the profession?
Continuity?

00:58:41.862 --> 00:58:45.902
Because something is there, right?
-Something is, that’s for sure.

00:58:46.380 --> 00:58:49.500
Croatia has incredible
results in football.

00:58:50.900 --> 00:58:54.700
Players who have left
an incredible mark,

00:58:54.910 --> 00:58:57.190
Well, you and everyone else.

00:58:57.382 --> 00:59:01.641
Ćiro Blažević and now this
national team led by Dalić.

00:59:03.380 --> 00:59:05.780
So, I think these are
fantastic results.

00:59:06.180 --> 00:59:09.620
We’re good at basketball, yes.
I don’t know what the secret is.

00:59:12.540 --> 00:59:15.011
I think it’s about the relationship
that the players have

00:59:15.145 --> 00:59:17.081
towards the national team.

00:59:17.302 --> 00:59:21.999
In both cases. Both in Croatian football
and my guys in basketball.

00:59:22.129 --> 00:59:23.679
It’s something incredible.

00:59:24.700 --> 00:59:27.980
They have the right leaders,
both among the coaches

00:59:28.094 --> 00:59:30.774
and among the players,
and then that gets passed down

00:59:30.912 --> 00:59:32.752
from generation to generation.

00:59:33.060 --> 00:59:36.820
I know that in Croatia there are
very good basketball players,

00:59:37.140 --> 00:59:39.820
but something is missing,
I really don’t know what.

00:59:41.180 --> 00:59:43.780
Just as Serbia has
outstanding football players,

00:59:43.940 --> 00:59:46.020
who play in various
European clubs,

00:59:46.260 --> 00:59:51.860
but never in the national team.
I’m good friends with Piksi.

00:59:52.060 --> 00:59:55.060
I know how dedicated he is,
I know how much he loves it.

00:59:55.220 --> 00:59:59.220
He is probably someone more
qualified to talk about it.

00:59:59.420 --> 01:00:02.220
When we look back
at his results,

01:00:03.060 --> 01:00:05.420
we’ll remember that Serbian
national team in football

01:00:05.620 --> 01:00:08.826
didn’t even make it to the Euro
or World Cup, but we succeeded.

01:00:09.980 --> 01:00:14.140
Tradition is something very important.
I believe that’s what I just said,

01:00:14.300 --> 01:00:16.020
it gets passed down
from coach to players,

01:00:16.220 --> 01:00:18.380
to new generations
of coaches and players.

01:00:18.580 --> 01:00:21.380
When there is continuity,
it’s much easier.

01:00:22.140 --> 01:00:25.220
I think that’s what it’s about.
For Serbia, at this moment,

01:00:25.460 --> 01:00:28.260
the best player in the world
is playing. Nikola Jokić.

01:00:28.780 --> 01:00:32.660
For Serbia, there is also a man
I coached and for whom I know

01:00:32.860 --> 01:00:37.260
what qualities he has as a leader.
That’s Bogdan Bogdanović.

01:00:37.399 --> 01:00:40.119
When he’s in the national team,
everything is immediately different.

01:00:40.272 --> 01:00:44.112
And all the others who realized that
those two are the two main leaders.

01:00:44.320 --> 01:00:46.680
And of course, we have
an experienced coach,

01:00:46.818 --> 01:00:49.964
a successful, outstanding coach
on the bench, Kari Pesic.

01:00:50.191 --> 01:00:54.231
All of that together leads to the fact
that the national team looks

01:00:54.383 --> 01:00:57.063
the way it does and that we are
all in the world of basketball

01:00:57.201 --> 01:00:58.721
extremely happy about it.

01:01:00.700 --> 01:01:03.700
What else but to wish them
to keep going like this.

01:01:03.980 --> 01:01:10.100
And wish the people from the football
national team to achieve the best results.

01:01:11.460 --> 01:01:14.340
A nation lives for sport.
We all know what it looks like

01:01:14.540 --> 01:01:16.860
at major competitions.

01:01:17.140 --> 01:01:22.077
People forget about the rivalry
between the clubs.

01:01:22.980 --> 01:01:25.620
Here, Partizan and Zvezda are rivals,
but when the national team plays,

01:01:25.820 --> 01:01:28.620
everyone cheers for the national team.
There are also arguments.

01:01:28.820 --> 01:01:31.700
Did this one play more, or that one...
But that gets forgotten.

01:01:31.900 --> 01:01:38.340
That’s probably something people
in one country, in one state,

01:01:38.580 --> 01:01:42.060
will always support always
support someone who gives

01:01:42.260 --> 01:01:44.500
their all playing
for the national team.

01:01:44.700 --> 01:01:47.860
I’ve been both a player and a coach,
but nothing could ever compare

01:01:48.100 --> 01:01:52.521
to preparing for the national team and being
a part of what the national team is.

01:01:52.624 --> 01:01:54.624
That’s why it’s called
like that-national team.

01:01:54.745 --> 01:01:56.325
You represent one country.
-That’s right.

01:01:56.543 --> 01:02:02.404
It’s the greatest honor and pleasure
that an athlete, player, or coach

01:02:02.623 --> 01:02:04.383
can experience in their career.
-Yes, that’s the peak.

01:02:04.615 --> 01:02:08.855
In football, we have
this responsibility that lasts.

01:02:09.260 --> 01:02:15.140
I remember when Ladić defended.
After 1998, he was 35 years old. -Yes.

01:02:15.372 --> 01:02:18.972
He wanted to retire,
but the whole country rebelled.

01:02:19.535 --> 01:02:27.666
At the same time, several players,
with club careers: "It doesn’t matter."

01:02:28.713 --> 01:02:32.424
Simply, that continues.
-It’s different.

01:02:32.900 --> 01:02:44.255
In basketball, you have the continuity.
It’s necessary to pass your knowledge.

01:02:46.103 --> 01:02:50.362
I’ve never run away from it and
it’s always been a pleasure for me.

01:02:50.600 --> 01:02:53.736
There are many famous players
whom I have coached,

01:02:54.580 --> 01:02:59.540
and whom I still coach today.
At some point, it becomes tiring.

01:02:59.682 --> 01:03:02.202
Not for me, but for the players.
I don’t have any problem.

01:03:02.418 --> 01:03:04.898
However, the atmosphere lasts
longer when the players see

01:03:05.154 --> 01:03:08.870
a lot of foreign faces.
"Who is this guy, why is he here..."

01:03:09.033 --> 01:03:10.644
Their concentration drops. -Yes.

01:03:11.220 --> 01:03:14.620
I always try those young coaches
at the seminar to provoke

01:03:14.900 --> 01:03:18.420
in order to an interaction happened.

01:03:18.900 --> 01:03:22.220
Because as soon as they don't ask
anything, that's not good.

01:03:22.460 --> 01:03:25.060
The last seminar, which was
held by our organization

01:03:25.260 --> 01:03:29.651
EuroLeague Coaches Association,
Dimitris and I did some offence.

01:03:30.298 --> 01:03:35.511
I do the offence,
and he does the defense.

01:03:37.105 --> 01:03:42.956
And then we made a change. He was
the attacker, and I was the defense.

01:03:43.266 --> 01:03:45.495
There are no secrets there.

01:03:46.960 --> 01:03:52.244
The biggest secret is to apply
what you have in you

01:03:52.947 --> 01:03:59.853
in relation to the quality
of the players. We talked about it...

01:04:01.796 --> 01:04:06.788
The influence of Guardiola,
before that Capello, Trapattoni.

01:04:07.780 --> 01:04:10.540
We all followed someone.

01:04:11.100 --> 01:04:18.559
The game model is a miracle,
it's just missing Messi or Ronaldo...

01:04:19.900 --> 01:04:27.700
Or Jokic. That coach gave him
that game model. -Yes.

01:04:28.500 --> 01:04:32.700
Now he's copying Sacramento,
that's what he's doing.

01:04:35.900 --> 01:04:38.940
It's the evolution of the game.

01:04:40.620 --> 01:04:45.220
This coach in Liverpool who
left is the famous coach Klopp...

01:04:45.398 --> 01:04:47.518
Everyone thought what are
we going to do now?

01:04:47.719 --> 01:04:50.079
Manchester after Ferguson,
who did miracles,

01:04:50.420 --> 01:04:53.980
it can’t be recovered
afterwards for 100 years.

01:04:55.380 --> 01:04:59.540
Top players and coaches,
money is invested in that club.

01:04:59.780 --> 01:05:04.180
But it isn’t money always
a guarantee in sports.

01:05:04.420 --> 01:05:07.300
It plays a very important role.
-That's right.

01:05:08.180 --> 01:05:11.060
Real Madrid is not the best,
because they have the money.

01:05:11.300 --> 01:05:16.100
Their matches have strong character.
The Bernabeu spirit.

01:05:17.180 --> 01:05:20.060
I really believe that.

01:05:20.300 --> 01:05:24.540
I was the coach of Real Madrid,
when I was 35 years old.

01:05:24.780 --> 01:05:29.340
But in football, it's unbelievable.
-It happened so many times...

01:05:29.900 --> 01:05:34.580
That there must be something.
Weird. -I have one more question.

01:05:36.140 --> 01:05:41.740
As this is a project for young people,
for parents, players and for everyone...

01:05:42.100 --> 01:05:46.180
Mostly for children,
what is your advice for parents,

01:05:46.460 --> 01:05:52.900
when they in those years,
and they leave junior school

01:05:53.180 --> 01:05:56.619
to professional sports, if they go?
You wanted to go on loan?

01:05:56.725 --> 01:05:58.470
That's right.
-The professor didn't allow.

01:05:58.596 --> 01:06:01.676
I was on two loans and it's easy
for me to say to the player:

01:06:02.171 --> 01:06:08.006
"It was me!" -Yes. -Young player
is young, only if he plays.

01:06:08.244 --> 01:06:13.852
If he doesn't play, he gets old.
-That's right. -In one or two years.

01:06:14.060 --> 01:06:17.460
You said it all. The most important
thing for young player is to play.

01:06:20.562 --> 01:06:26.002
I know how much I suffer,
as a coach and as a man,

01:06:26.500 --> 01:06:30.940
when every player can't play
in that game. But it happens.

01:06:31.460 --> 01:06:35.460
The last game was played
by 8 players while rotating them.

01:06:35.660 --> 01:06:39.340
We played to win, but I'm sad,
when I stay alone, I think…

01:06:39.580 --> 01:06:43.340
"Why didn't i give everyone
a chance?" I can't...

01:06:43.540 --> 01:06:49.100
But I'm thinking about next game.
I'll give you that chance. Be prepared!

01:06:49.340 --> 01:06:51.940
Especially, for a young player.
And always I say:

01:06:52.180 --> 01:06:57.663
"Go, play in another league,
or in another club, just play!"

01:06:57.797 --> 01:06:59.597
And that's the only advice.

01:06:59.782 --> 01:07:03.609
Advice for parents is, let the kids
to develop, children are smart.

01:07:03.825 --> 01:07:07.825
Don’t solve through children
your life problems. -Yes.

01:07:08.952 --> 01:07:10.020
Well done!

01:07:12.500 --> 01:07:18.340
For children to believe that
there are no limits to a man.

01:07:18.740 --> 01:07:21.500
But there are no
guarantees either. -No.

01:07:21.780 --> 01:07:26.580
Do you know what Nikola Pilić said?
That's a phenomenal statement.

01:07:26.820 --> 01:07:28.700
I was a selector...

01:07:28.980 --> 01:07:34.340
When he was asked, in tennis,
since that is an individual sport,

01:07:34.580 --> 01:07:40.380
can it be more easily judged
whether some 17-year-old

01:07:40.534 --> 01:07:42.334
to be the new Becker?

01:07:43.140 --> 01:07:49.972
No, I can only know who won't be
the new Becker. That's genius.

01:07:50.980 --> 01:07:56.660
Is it true that Jokić passed
under scout  radar?

01:07:56.880 --> 01:08:02.860
Is it true that he was not recognized?
-I watched the European Championship.

01:08:03.140 --> 01:08:08.100
I was not working that year. That was
in the Czech Republic, in Prague...

01:08:08.380 --> 01:08:10.860
When they played the finals
against the Americans

01:08:11.140 --> 01:08:14.940
in the World Championship,
Micić and Jokić.

01:08:15.620 --> 01:08:19.860
Of course, the American National Team
played pressing the entire game.

01:08:20.340 --> 01:08:23.860
We held on well until a certain
moment and then...

01:08:24.100 --> 01:08:28.797
The best player of that
World Junior Championship

01:08:29.039 --> 01:08:35.010
was this player who playes
with Jokic, in Denver, Gordon.

01:08:38.900 --> 01:08:41.180
Now, they are incomparable.

01:08:41.420 --> 01:08:45.460
Why he was the best?
He was physically dominant.

01:08:45.940 --> 01:08:52.100
Nikola wasn't, and isn't now,
but he is still there on physical level,

01:08:52.340 --> 01:08:56.020
and Nicola is the fastest
player in the world.

01:08:56.220 --> 01:08:59.140
He makes decisions
before anyone else.

01:08:59.460 --> 01:09:03.780
He plays, as I said, chess.
Man is a computer.

01:09:03.980 --> 01:09:09.500
It's amazing what he does. Amazing!
Amazing basketball intelligence.

01:09:09.700 --> 01:09:14.740
He differs in that. Those
shots of his are not accidental.

01:09:15.060 --> 01:09:19.907
He's working on it.
That's what everyone says.

01:09:20.193 --> 01:09:21.913
I was surprised...

01:09:22.745 --> 01:09:28.126
Three or four years ago I held
a seminar in Opatija with Partizan.

01:09:28.537 --> 01:09:32.897
I saw him, because they had
a presentation at the same time.

01:09:33.262 --> 01:09:36.502
I greet him and say: "Where are you,
Nikola, how are you, master?"

01:09:36.773 --> 01:09:40.293
He says: "Coach, I watched
your seminar from Opatija."

01:09:40.760 --> 01:09:45.984
I agree with 95% of things,
and for those 5% they tell me:

01:09:46.222 --> 01:09:48.982
"You disagree, Nikola not
even with yourself".

01:09:49.538 --> 01:09:54.586
I was incredibly surprised that
he watched my seminar.

01:09:54.822 --> 01:09:58.222
I'm talking about dedication,
he was watching some seminar...

01:09:58.407 --> 01:10:01.167
The best player in the world,
who dominates...

01:10:01.400 --> 01:10:04.400
So, he likes basketball,
he lives for that basketball.

01:10:04.940 --> 01:10:08.660
As incredible as it may seem,
he hates talking to journalists.

01:10:09.980 --> 01:10:14.860
It can be seen in his every
movement, how dedicated he is.

01:10:15.300 --> 01:10:19.860
As you said, there is work,
there is also talent.

01:10:20.100 --> 01:10:27.140
Gordon was recognized, Jokić wasn’t.
Does it seem that talent is underrated?

01:10:28.220 --> 01:10:36.540
Of course, work is work,
if you're not talented, it's hard.

01:10:37.260 --> 01:10:44.100
I agree, someone has talent
when he copies someone who is best.

01:10:44.300 --> 01:10:46.140
That's talent number one.

01:10:46.380 --> 01:10:49.580
No talent isn't enough, if player
doesn't continue to work.

01:10:49.780 --> 01:10:51.540
And the one who works,
and don’t have talent,

01:10:51.740 --> 01:10:55.940
reached a certain level.
So, that's the balance.

01:10:56.216 --> 01:10:58.810
If you're have talent, and you
work on it, then it's a miracle.

01:10:59.029 --> 01:11:03.393
Jokic is that. -Jokić? -And Bogdanović,
Bojan Bogdanović, too.

01:11:03.505 --> 01:11:05.526
They all ended up there.

01:11:05.740 --> 01:11:11.627
I was lucky to play with: Toni
Kukoč, late Dražen, Divac,

01:11:11.918 --> 01:11:16.268
Paljo, Rađa, Danilović, Đorđević...

01:11:17.365 --> 01:11:26.126
During Yugoslavia, the talent
was neglected and belittled.

01:11:26.420 --> 01:11:30.060
Work was despised, it was,
"let them run, we know"...

01:11:30.620 --> 01:11:34.820
It seems to me that today everything
is measured by physical parameters.

01:11:35.620 --> 01:11:40.020
Sport has changed, it's getting
faster, players are stronger.

01:11:40.561 --> 01:11:43.601
However, I watched my players.

01:11:43.841 --> 01:11:48.348
There are some rubber bands
everywhere, they stretch...

01:11:48.721 --> 01:11:54.761
One day we practiced penalty kicks.
The game begins, three out of twelve.

01:11:55.220 --> 01:11:58.820
I tell them to leave rubber bands
and take the ball.

01:11:59.060 --> 01:12:03.220
It's basketball, the ball need to go
through the hoop, forget that.

01:12:03.460 --> 01:12:08.580
But, of course, in this training
process, games and traveling,

01:12:09.060 --> 01:12:14.353
players must take care of their bodies,
everything is clear why it is done.

01:12:15.111 --> 01:12:19.060
The essence of sport is what I said,
when a player enters the court,

01:12:19.300 --> 01:12:22.420
doesn't take his stand,
but takes a shot.

01:12:22.558 --> 01:12:24.839
As many shots as possible,
it is easier later on.

01:12:25.036 --> 01:12:28.613
This is how self-confidence is gained.
When your arm start hurting.

01:12:28.728 --> 01:12:30.448
That's what Kića said...

01:12:30.563 --> 01:12:33.691
"I didn't go out until my arm hurt,
when it hurts, then I leave".

01:12:33.923 --> 01:12:38.214
It doesn't matter if it's 500 or 1000.
Who was the best freekicker?

01:12:38.856 --> 01:12:41.636
The one who stayed and worked.

01:12:42.053 --> 01:12:45.773
And who did bicycle dribbling
in football. -Exactly.

01:12:46.224 --> 01:12:52.003
That's automatism. -That's what
you are saying a moment ago...

01:12:52.259 --> 01:12:54.339
That dedication or whatever to do.

01:12:54.815 --> 01:13:00.894
Even if you are Jordan, Modrić,
Obradović, Ronaldo, Tesla, De Niro...

01:13:02.540 --> 01:13:07.982
That dedication, that's not work,
that's obsession, obsessiveness.

01:13:08.152 --> 01:13:10.490
We can name it that.
-That's right, that's it.

01:13:11.672 --> 01:13:14.700
Željko, in the end I have
to say something...

01:13:16.940 --> 01:13:23.500
You are truly unique.
I don't make a mistery out my work.

01:13:24.115 --> 01:13:29.642
I deal with it. Successfull people
have some luck at a given moment.

01:13:30.065 --> 01:13:33.825
Some more, some less,
some are better at some things,

01:13:34.740 --> 01:13:38.180
and some are better at other things,
but you are unique.

01:13:38.980 --> 01:13:47.660
You are the most trophy-winning
coach in ball sports,

01:13:49.460 --> 01:13:55.300
and an extraordinary man.
Unique and complete.

01:13:55.860 --> 01:13:59.700
And you are, at the same time,
cold and decisive,

01:14:00.580 --> 01:14:08.180
but warm and paternal,
calculated and pragmatic.

01:14:08.980 --> 01:14:13.900
But, also you are emotionally
and passionate, rational and intuitive.

01:14:14.180 --> 01:14:17.020
It's hard to explain,
except to say that you are complete.

01:14:17.260 --> 01:14:21.540
You know who explained it best,
Duško Vujošević.

01:14:22.620 --> 01:14:30.312
A great coach and man
with wise thinking, he said…

01:14:33.300 --> 01:14:39.836
"I have a friend Voja Stanić,
98-year-old painter.

01:14:40.820 --> 01:14:51.460
Vojo says that a man should live two
lives. The first life, to live and to sin.

01:14:51.860 --> 01:14:56.900
And other, to live properly,
without failure.

01:14:57.380 --> 01:15:01.780
This is another life for Željko.
All this what is happening to him,

01:15:02.020 --> 01:15:06.340
how he behaves, as agreed,
decisions which he makes,

01:15:06.660 --> 01:15:09.580
he already lived."
That's just the way it is.

01:15:09.860 --> 01:15:14.455
Yes, I know about that statement.
Thanks, I was going to interrupt you.

01:15:14.698 --> 01:15:19.737
With so many compliments
I will look like I do in my games.

01:15:20.300 --> 01:15:23.420
You are embarrasing me...
Thank you very much.

01:15:23.700 --> 01:15:26.860
This isn’t your first time
to talk about me like that.

01:15:27.100 --> 01:15:31.500
I know, when you were in Turkey,
when you gave those statements.

01:15:31.780 --> 01:15:36.780
In the great city of Istanbul,
due to obligations we had,

01:15:37.020 --> 01:15:39.740
we didn't manage to see each other.

01:15:40.180 --> 01:15:45.060
Thanks to the people who are
leading this phenomenal project.

01:15:45.300 --> 01:15:48.380
It is an incredible pleasure
to talk to you.

01:15:48.620 --> 01:15:54.660
Indeed, as I said, it is no joke,
you are extremely talented for this job.

01:15:55.300 --> 01:15:59.646
You have experiences that are rare.

01:16:00.700 --> 01:16:03.940
Once again, thank you
for your wonderful words.

01:16:04.180 --> 01:16:07.540
I hope that this project,
in which you and I participate,

01:16:07.780 --> 01:16:10.220
will be better and better
and that it will bring

01:16:10.500 --> 01:16:14.500
young people closer together.
It’s the most valuable idea of ​​all.

01:16:15.780 --> 01:16:20.180
That these spaces get another dimension.
So that we can all succeed together,

01:16:20.460 --> 01:16:23.700
to get to know each other and
hang out as much as possible.

01:16:23.900 --> 01:16:25.540
Thank you, Željko. -Thank you.

